      'Note: SSS has been transitioning to the MySSS Card (formerly UMID). Check with your SSS branch for the latest card type being issued',
      'Set an appointment online to avoid very long walk-in queues, especially at Metro Manila branches',
      'Make sure your SSS records (name, birthdate, address) are updated and match your valid ID before applying',
      'Bring your original IDs \u2014 photocopies are not accepted for UMID applications',
      'If your UMID is lost, report it immediately to SSS and apply for a replacement',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'SSS Official Website', url: 'https://www.sss.gov.ph/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'My.SSS Portal', url: 'https://member.sss.gov.ph/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'SSS UMID Card Guidelines', url: 'https://www.sss.gov.ph/'),
    ],
  ),
  'passport': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'passport',
    title: 'Get a Philippine Passport',
    description: 'Your passport is the most universally accepted ID in the Philippines and the world \u2014 it\'s your key to international travel.',
    why: 'Even if you don\'t plan to travel abroad soon, having a passport gives you the most powerful ID for banking, visa applications, and official transactions. Valid for 10 years (adults).',
    how: 'Schedule an appointment at dfa.gov.ph/passport. Prepare: PSA birth certificate, valid government ID, accomplished application form. Processing is 12 business days (regular) or 6 days (expedited). Cost: \u20B1950 (regular) or \u20B11,200 (expedited).',
    priority: 'important',
    requirements: [
      'PSA-authenticated Certificate of Live Birth (original and photocopy) on security paper',
      'One (1) valid government-issued ID with photo (driver\'s license, UMID, PhilSys National ID, PRC ID, voter\'s ID)',
      'Confirmed DFA online appointment (walk-ins are NOT allowed except for emergencies)',
      'Printed appointment confirmation page or saved on your phone',
      'For late-registered birth certificates (registered less than 10 years ago): additional NBI Clearance and IDs that pre-date the late registration',
      'For married applicants: PSA marriage certificate',
      'Personal appearance required \u2014 no representatives allowed',
    ],
    steps: [
      'Step 1: Go to passport.gov.ph and create an account or log in',
      'Step 2: Click \'Schedule an Appointment\' and choose between new application or renewal',
      'Step 3: Select your preferred DFA office (consular office or satellite office), date, and time slot',
      'Step 4: Choose processing type \u2014 Regular (\u20B1950) or Expedited (\u20B11,200)',
      'Step 5: Pay the passport fee online via Bayad Center, 7-Eleven, GCash, Maya, or credit/debit card',
      'Step 6: Print or save your confirmed appointment page with the reference number and QR code',
      'Step 7: On your appointment date, arrive at least 30 minutes early at the DFA office',
      'Step 8: Present your appointment confirmation and requirements at the receiving window',
      'Step 9: Proceed to encoding \u2014 your personal details will be entered into the system',
      'Step 10: Biometric capture \u2014 photo, fingerprints, and digital signature',
      'Step 11: Review the printed data sheet for any errors before signing',
      'Step 12: Receive your claim stub indicating the release date',
      'Step 13: Pick up your passport on the indicated release date, or opt for courier delivery (additional fee)',
    ],
    fees: '\u20B1950 (regular processing) or \u20B11,200 (expedited processing). Courier delivery: additional \u20B1150-300 depending on location',
    processingTime: 'Metro Manila: 10 working days (regular), 5 working days (expedited). Outside Metro Manila: 12 working days (regular), 7 working days (expedited). Foreign Service Posts: 4-6 weeks',
    tips: [
      'Appointments fill up fast \u2014 book at least 2-4 weeks in advance, especially during peak travel months (March-June, November-December)',
      'DFA releases new appointment slots every day at midnight \u2014 check early for the best dates',
      'Dress neatly and avoid wearing white or light-colored tops for your passport photo (the background is white)',
      'Remove earrings, eyeglasses, and colored contact lenses for the photo',
      'The passport is valid for 10 years for adults (18+) and 5 years for minors',
      'If your PSA birth certificate has errors, fix them at the PSA or Local Civil Registrar BEFORE your passport appointment',
      'Courtesy lane is available for senior citizens, PWDs, pregnant women, and solo parents \u2014 bring supporting documents',
      'Keep a scanned copy of your passport\'s data page on your phone and in cloud storage for emergencies',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'DFA Passport Appointment System', url: 'https://www.passport.gov.ph/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'DFA Passport Requirements (New Adult)', url: 'https://consular.dfa.gov.ph/adult-new/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'DFA Passport FAQ', url: 'https://consular.dfa.gov.ph/passport-faq/'),
    ],
  ),
  'drivers-license': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'drivers-license',
    title: 'Get a Driver\'s License (LTO)',
    description: 'A non-professional driver\'s license lets you legally drive a private vehicle and is a widely accepted government ID.',
    why: 'Required by law to drive. Also one of the most accepted IDs for banking and government transactions. Valid for 5 years.',
    how: 'Step 1: Get a Student Permit at LTO \u2014 bring PSA birth certificate, valid ID, medical certificate, and pass the written exam. Step 2: After holding a student permit, apply for a non-professional license with a practical driving test. Process at lto.gov.ph or any LTO office.',
    priority: 'good-to-have',
    requirements: [
      'Must be at least 16 years old for Student Permit, 17 years old for Non-Professional License',
      'PSA-issued birth certificate (original and photocopy)',
      'One (1) valid government-issued ID (PhilSys National ID, passport, UMID, TIN card, voter\'s ID)',
      'Medical certificate from an LTO-accredited clinic (physical and drug test)',
      'Completion certificate for the 15-hour Theoretical Driving Course (TDC) from an LTO-accredited driving school',
      'Completion certificate for the Practical Driving Course (PDC) \u2014 required for non-professional license',
      'Student Permit held for at least 30 days (to apply for non-professional license)',
      'No unsettled traffic violations',
    ],
    steps: [
      'PHASE 1: STUDENT PERMIT',
      'Step 1: Get a medical certificate from an LTO-accredited medical clinic (usually located near LTO offices). Cost: \u20B1350-\u20B1500',
      'Step 2: Complete the 15-hour Theoretical Driving Course (TDC) at an LTO-accredited driving school. You\'ll receive a TDC completion certificate',
      'Step 3: Visit your nearest LTO District/Licensing Office and get an Application for Permits and Licenses (APL) form',
      'Step 4: Fill out the APL form and submit with your requirements at the evaluation counter',
      'Step 5: Pay the student permit fee (approximately \u20B1317.63 \u2014 includes application, computer, and permit fees)',
      'Step 6: Have your photo and biometrics captured',
      'Step 7: Take the theoretical (written) exam \u2014 you must pass to receive your Student Permit',
      'Step 8: Receive your Student Permit (valid for 1 year)',
      'PHASE 2: NON-PROFESSIONAL LICENSE (after 30+ days with Student Permit)',
      'Step 9: Complete the Practical Driving Course (PDC) at an LTO-accredited driving school',
      'Step 10: Return to an LTO office with your Student Permit, PDC completion certificate, and other requirements',
      'Step 11: Fill out a new APL form for Non-Professional License',
      'Step 12: Take the practical driving test at the LTO office',
      'Step 13: If you pass, pay the license fee (approximately \u20B1585 + \u20B167.63 computer fee)',
      'Step 14: Have your photo and biometrics captured for the license card',
      'Step 15: Receive your Non-Professional Driver\'s License',
    ],
    fees: 'Student Permit: ~\u20B1317.63 (application + computer + permit fees). Non-Professional License: ~\u20B1652.63 (license + computer fees). Medical certificate: \u20B1350-\u20B1500. TDC: \u20B12,000-\u20B14,000. PDC: \u20B13,000-\u20B18,000. Total estimated cost: \u20B16,000-\u20B113,000+',
    processingTime: 'Student Permit: same day (if you pass the exam). Non-Professional License: same day (if you pass the driving test). Minimum 30 days must pass between getting Student Permit and applying for license',
    tips: [
      'Complete TDC and medical exam BEFORE visiting LTO \u2014 you cannot apply without these',
      'Schedule your LTO visit early in the morning (offices open at 8AM) to avoid long queues',
      'Some LTO offices have online appointment systems \u2014 check lto.gov.ph for availability',
      'Study for the theoretical exam using the LTO Reviewer app or practice exams online',
      'The practical driving test includes starting on an incline, parallel parking, and navigating an obstacle course',
      'Your non-professional license is valid for 5 years, with potential 10-year validity if you maintain a clean driving record',
      'You CANNOT drive alone with just a Student Permit \u2014 a licensed driver must accompany you at all times',
      'Keep your medical certificate fresh \u2014 it\'s only valid for 30 days from issuance for LTO purposes',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'LTO Official Website', url: 'https://lto.gov.ph/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'LTO Driver\'s License Guide', url: 'https://ltoportal.org/drivers-license/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'LTO Student Permit Requirements', url: 'https://ltoportal.org/lto-student-permit/'),
    ],
  ),
  'voters-id': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'voters-id',
    title: 'Register as a Voter (COMELEC)',
    description: 'Voter registration gives you the right to vote in national and local elections \u2014 and your voter\'s certificate is accepted as a valid ID.',
    why: 'Voting is your civic duty and your voice in shaping the Philippines. Local elections directly affect your community, schools, roads, and health services. Registration is free.',
    how: 'Register at the COMELEC office in your municipality/city. Bring a valid ID and proof of residency. Online pre-registration is available at voterregistration.comelec.gov.ph. Registration periods open before every election.',
    priority: 'important',
    requirements: [
      'Must be at least 18 years old on or before election day',
      'Must have resided in the Philippines for at least one (1) year and in the city/municipality where you intend to register for at least six (6) months before the election',
      'One (1) valid government-issued ID with photo (PhilSys National ID, SSS/GSIS/UMID, passport, driver\'s license, PRC ID, postal ID)',
      'Note: Cedulas (Community Tax Certificates), PNP clearance, and employee IDs are NOT accepted',
      'If no valid ID: a registered voter from your precinct or a relative within the 4th civil degree can identify you under oath',
      'Must not be disqualified from voting by law (e.g., convicted of a crime involving disloyalty to the government, insanity)',
    ],
    steps: [
      'Step 1: Check if voter registration is currently open \u2014 COMELEC opens registration periods before elections (check comelec.gov.ph for schedules)',
      'Step 2: Download the CEF-1 (Application for Registration) form from comelec.gov.ph, or get one at the Office of the Election Officer (OEO) in your city/municipality',
      'Step 3: Fill out the form completely \u2014 use black ink and print legibly. Include your full name, address, birthdate, and other personal details',
      'Step 4: Visit the OEO (COMELEC office) in the city/municipality where you intend to vote',
      'Step 5: Submit your accomplished CEF-1 form and present your valid ID',
      'Step 6: Have your biometrics captured \u2014 photo, fingerprints, and signature',
      'Step 7: Your application will be reviewed and included in the list of voters for your precinct',
      'Step 8: Check the COMELEC website or visit the OEO to confirm your registration was approved and to find your precinct assignment',
      'Step 9: On election day, bring your voter\'s ID or any valid ID to your assigned precinct to vote',
    ],
    fees: 'Free \u2014 voter registration has no fees',
    processingTime: 'Registration: same day (biometrics and application submission). Approval and precinct assignment: processed during the registration period. Voter\'s ID/certification: varies',
    tips: [
      'Registration periods are limited \u2014 don\'t wait until the last day. COMELEC typically opens registration 1-2 years before a national election',
      'If you\'ve moved to a new city/municipality, you need to transfer your registration \u2014 file a transfer application at the OEO of your new residence',
      'You can check your voter registration status online at comelec.gov.ph using the Precinct Finder',
      'The Voter\'s ID is a valid government-issued ID accepted for many transactions',
      'Deactivated voters (those who failed to vote in two consecutive elections) must re-register',
      'Arrive early at the OEO \u2014 registration centers can get very crowded, especially near deadline dates',
      'Overseas Filipinos can register for overseas absentee voting at Philippine embassies or consulates',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'COMELEC Official Website', url: 'https://comelec.gov.ph/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'COMELEC Registration Requirements', url: 'https://comelec.gov.ph/?r=VoterRegistration/WhatisVoterRegistration/RegistrationRequirements'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'COMELEC How to Register', url: 'https://comelec.gov.ph/?r=VoterRegistration/HowtoRegister'),
    ],
  ),
  'first-time-jobseeker': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'first-time-jobseeker',
    title: 'Get your First Time Jobseeker Certificate',
    description: 'A barangay certificate that exempts first-time job seekers from paying fees for government documents needed for employment.',
    why: 'Republic Act 11261 (First Time Jobseekers Assistance Act) exempts you from paying documentary requirements for your first employment \u2014 including NBI clearance, police clearance, barangay clearance, and others. This saves you \u20B1500\u2013\u20B11,500 in fees.',
    how: 'Visit your Barangay Hall and request a First Time Jobseeker Certificate. Bring a valid ID and fill out the application form. The certificate is valid for 1 year from issuance.',
    priority: 'critical',
    requirements: [
      'Any valid ID (school ID, birth certificate, voter\'s ID, or barangay ID)',
      'Filled-out oath of undertaking (provided at the barangay hall)',
      'Must be a resident of the barangay where you\'re applying',
      'Must be 18 years old and above',
      'Must not have been previously employed (this is for first-time job seekers only)',
    ],
    steps: [
      'Go to your Barangay Hall during office hours (usually 8 AM \u2013 5 PM, Monday to Friday)',
      'Ask for the First Time Jobseeker Certificate application at the barangay secretary\'s office',
      'Fill out the application form and the Oath of Undertaking \u2014 this is your sworn statement that you\'re a first-time jobseeker',
      'Submit the form with a photocopy of your valid ID',
      'Wait for processing \u2014 usually takes 15-30 minutes',
      'Receive your certificate. Keep the original and make 3-4 photocopies',
      'Use the certificate when applying for: NBI Clearance (free), Police Clearance (free), Barangay Clearance (free), PSA Birth Certificate (free), and other employment requirements',
    ],
    fees: 'Free \u2014 the certificate itself is free. It also exempts you from fees on other documents',
    processingTime: 'Same day \u2014 usually 15-30 minutes',
    tips: [
      'Get this BEFORE applying for NBI clearance, police clearance, or any other employment documents \u2014 it exempts you from their fees',
      'The certificate is valid for 1 year. If you don\'t find a job within that period, you can renew it',
      'Make multiple photocopies \u2014 you\'ll need to present it at each government office where you claim exemption',
      'Some barangays may ask you to return the next day for signing by the barangay captain. Call ahead to check',
      'This only applies to your FIRST employment. Freelance work or online jobs may or may not count depending on the barangay\'s interpretation',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'RA 11261 Full Text (First Time Jobseekers Act)', url: 'https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/2019/04/10/republic-act-no-11261/'),
    ],
  ),

  // ─── Phase 2: Banking & Emergency Fund ──────────────────────────────────────
  'savings-account': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'savings-account',
    title: 'Open a bank savings account',
    description: 'A traditional savings account at BDO, BPI, Metrobank, or UnionBank gives you access to ATMs nationwide, checks, and formal banking services.',
    why: 'Cash under a mattress earns nothing and can be stolen. A savings account is the baseline for receiving payroll, paying bills, and accessing the financial system. Required for most loan applications.',
    how: 'Visit any branch with two valid IDs and an initial deposit (BPI: \u20B13,000; BDO: \u20B12,000; UnionBank: \u20B10). UnionBank\'s EON account and BDO\'s account can be opened fully online. Choose a bank near your home or office.',
    priority: 'critical',
    appLink: '/accounts',
    appLinkLabel: 'Track in Accounts',
    requirements: [
      'Two (2) valid government-issued IDs with photo (passport, driver\'s license, UMID, PhilSys National ID, PRC ID, voter\'s ID, postal ID)',
      'TIN (Tax Identification Number) \u2014 required by most banks even if unemployed',
      'Proof of billing address: latest utility bill (electricity, water, internet, phone) or credit card statement \u2014 must show your name and address',
      'Initial deposit amount (varies by bank: BPI \u20B13,000, BDO \u20B12,000, Metrobank \u20B12,000, UnionBank \u20B10 for EON, Security Bank \u20B15,000-\u20B110,000)',
      'Active mobile number and email address',
      'For online account opening: smartphone with camera for selfie verification',
    ],
    steps: [
      'Step 1: Choose a bank based on branch proximity, ATM network, minimum balance requirements, and fees. Top choices for first-timers: BPI, BDO, UnionBank, or Metrobank',
      'Step 2 (In-Branch): Visit the nearest branch during banking hours (typically 9AM-3PM weekdays)',
      'Step 3: Get a queue number for \'New Accounts\' and wait for your turn',
      'Step 4: Fill out the multi-page application form (Customer Information Sheet) \u2014 provide personal info, employment details, source of funds, and TIN',
      'Step 5: Submit the form with your two valid IDs. The bank officer will verify and photocopy your documents',
      'Step 6: The bank may ask clarifying questions about your employment, income source, and purpose of the account',
      'Step 7: Make your initial deposit at the cashier',
      'Step 8: Receive your passbook and/or ATM card (some banks issue ATM cards immediately, others mail them within 5-7 days)',
      'Step 9: Activate your online/mobile banking by downloading the bank\'s app and registering your account',
      'Alternative (Online): Banks like UnionBank (EON), BPI, and BDO allow fully online account opening \u2014 download the app, scan your ID, take a selfie, and fund via InstaPay',
    ],
    fees: 'Account opening: Free. Maintaining balance varies (BPI: \u20B13,000, BDO: \u20B12,000, Metrobank: \u20B110,000). Below-minimum balance fee: \u20B1300/month. ATM card replacement: \u20B1150-\u20B1350. Some accounts have zero maintaining balance (e.g., UnionBank EON, BPI Save-Up)',
    processingTime: 'In-branch: 30-60 minutes (same day). Online account opening: 5-15 minutes (may take 1-2 business days for full verification)',
    tips: [
      'Choose a bank with many ATMs near your home and office to avoid withdrawal fees (\u20B118-\u20B125 per transaction at other bank ATMs)',
      'UnionBank EON is excellent as a first account \u2014 zero maintaining balance, free online transfers, and fully online opening',
      'Always set up online/mobile banking immediately \u2014 it saves you from branch visits for transfers and bill payments',
      'Keep your maintaining balance above the minimum to avoid the \u20B1300/month penalty fee',
      'Set up your payroll to deposit directly into your bank account \u2014 ask HR for the bank enrollment form',
      'PDIC (Philippine Deposit Insurance Corporation) insures deposits up to \u20B1500,000 per depositor per bank',
      'Compare interest rates \u2014 most traditional banks offer only 0.10-0.25% p.a. on regular savings',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'BPI Account Opening Requirements', url: 'https://www.bpi.com.ph/personal/bank/list-of-account-opening-requirements'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'BDO Personal Accounts', url: 'https://www.bdo.com.ph/personal'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'Security Bank Documents Needed', url: 'https://www.securitybank.com/blog/documents-you-need-to-open-a-bank-account-in-the-philippines/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'PDIC Deposit Insurance', url: 'https://www.pdic.gov.ph/'),
    ],
  ),
  'digital-savings': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'digital-savings',
    title: 'Open a high-yield digital savings account',
    description: 'ING (4% p.a.), CIMB (4.5% p.a.), and Maya (3.5% p.a.) offer savings rates far above traditional banks, with no maintaining balance.',
    why: 'Traditional banks pay 0.10\u20130.25% interest. Digital banks pay 3\u20135%. On \u20B150,000 in emergency funds, that\'s the difference between \u20B1125/year vs. \u20B12,000/year \u2014 with zero maintaining balance.',
    how: 'Download the app: ING Philippines, CIMB Bank, Maya, or Tonik. Sign up with a selfie + valid ID (passport or PhilSys). Account opens in minutes. Transfer money via InstaPay (\u20B150 fee, unless free with your sending bank).',
    priority: 'important',
    appLink: '/accounts',
    appLinkLabel: 'Track in Accounts',
    requirements: [
      'A smartphone (Android or iOS) with internet connection',
      'One (1) valid government-issued ID (PhilSys National ID, passport, driver\'s license, UMID, PRC ID, voter\'s ID, postal ID)',
      'Active mobile number (for OTP verification)',
      'Active email address',
      'Selfie for identity verification (taken in-app during registration)',
      'No minimum deposit required for most digital banks',
    ],
    steps: [
      'Step 1: Choose a digital bank based on interest rates and features. Top options: Maya Bank (up to 8% p.a. on Personal Goals), Tonik (up to 6% p.a. on time deposits), GoTyme (up to 5% p.a.), GCash/CIMB GSave (up to 4% p.a.)',
      'Step 2: Download the digital bank\'s app from Google Play Store or Apple App Store',
      'Step 3: Open the app and tap \'Sign Up\' or \'Create Account\'',
      'Step 4: Enter your mobile number and verify via OTP (one-time password)',
      'Step 5: Fill out personal details \u2014 full name, birthdate, address, email, source of funds',
      'Step 6: Upload or scan your valid government ID using your phone\'s camera',
      'Step 7: Take a selfie for identity verification \u2014 follow in-app instructions for proper lighting and angle',
      'Step 8: Review and submit your application',
      'Step 9: Wait for verification \u2014 most digital banks approve within minutes, some may take up to 24 hours',
      'Step 10: Once approved, you can start depositing via InstaPay, PESONet, or fund transfer from your existing bank account',
      'For GCash GSave: Open GCash app > tap \'Save Money\' > GSave > \'Open a GSave Account\' > follow prompts to create CIMB savings account within GCash',
    ],
    fees: 'No account opening fee. No maintaining balance. No closing fee. Fund transfers via InstaPay: Free or \u20B125-\u20B150 depending on the sending bank/app',
    processingTime: 'Account opening: 5-15 minutes. Verification: instant to 24 hours. Account fully usable immediately upon approval',
    tips: [
      'Digital banks are regulated by the Bangko Sentral ng Pilipinas (BSP) and deposits are insured by PDIC up to \u20B11,000,000 per depositor per bank \u2014 your money is safe',
      'Use digital bank accounts for your emergency fund \u2014 higher interest rates mean your money grows faster',
      'Maya Bank\'s Personal Goals feature lets you create up to 5 sub-accounts for different savings goals (e.g., emergency fund, travel, gadget)',
      'Interest rates change frequently \u2014 check the latest rates before opening. Promotional rates may be temporary',
      'You can link most digital bank accounts to e-wallets (GCash, Maya) for easy transfers',
      'Don\'t put all your money in one digital bank \u2014 spread across 2-3 to maximize PDIC insurance coverage and take advantage of different promo rates',
      'Set up auto-transfer from your payroll bank to your digital savings \u2014 automate the habit of saving',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'Maya Bank Savings', url: 'https://www.mayabank.ph/savings/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'Tonik Digital Bank', url: 'https://tonik.com/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'GoTyme Bank', url: 'https://www.gotyme.com.ph/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'BSP List of Digital Banks', url: 'https://www.bsp.gov.ph/Pages/InclusiveFinance/DigitalBanks.aspx'),
    ],
  ),
  'emergency-fund-3mo': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'emergency-fund-3mo',
    title: 'Save 3 months of living expenses',
    description: 'Your emergency fund covers job loss, medical emergencies, car repairs, or any unexpected expense \u2014 without going into debt.',
    why: 'Without an emergency fund, any unexpected expense forces you to borrow (credit card, 5-6 loan). The average Filipino salary takes 3\u20136 months to find a new job. Your emergency fund is your self-insurance.',
    how: 'Calculate your monthly expenses (rent + food + transport + utilities + insurance). Multiply by 3. Keep this in a separate high-yield savings account \u2014 don\'t mix it with your spending money. Automate a monthly transfer.',
    priority: 'critical',
    appLink: '/goals',
    appLinkLabel: 'Set Goal',
    requirements: [
      'A clear list of your essential monthly expenses (rent, food, transportation, utilities, insurance premiums, loan payments)',
      'A separate savings account dedicated ONLY to your emergency fund (preferably a high-yield digital bank)',
      'A commitment to consistent monthly savings \u2014 even small amounts count',
      'Knowledge of your monthly take-home pay (net salary after deductions)',
    ],
    steps: [
      'Step 1: List all your essential monthly expenses \u2014 rent/housing, food/groceries, transportation, utilities (electricity, water, internet, phone), insurance premiums, loan payments, and any other non-negotiable costs',
      'Step 2: Add them up to get your total monthly essential expenses. Example: \u20B18,000 rent + \u20B16,000 food + \u20B13,000 transport + \u20B12,000 utilities + \u20B11,000 insurance = \u20B120,000/month',
      'Step 3: Multiply by 3 to get your 3-month emergency fund target. Example: \u20B120,000 x 3 = \u20B160,000',
      'Step 4: Open a separate high-yield digital savings account (Maya, Tonik, GoTyme) exclusively for your emergency fund \u2014 do NOT mix it with your spending money',
      'Step 5: Determine how much you can save per month. Use the 50-30-20 rule: 50% needs, 30% savings, 20% wants. If that\'s too aggressive, start with 10-20% of your income',
      'Step 6: Break down your target into monthly chunks. Example: \u20B160,000 target \u00F7 12 months = \u20B15,000/month. If that\'s too much, extend the timeline \u2014 even \u20B12,000/month gets you there in 30 months',
      'Step 7: Automate your savings \u2014 set up an auto-transfer from your payroll bank to your emergency fund account on payday',
      'Step 8: Track your progress monthly. Celebrate milestones (\u20B110,000, \u20B130,000, goal reached!)',
      'Step 9: Once you reach 3 months, keep going to 6 months for full financial security',
      'Step 10: If you ever use your emergency fund, prioritize replenishing it immediately',
    ],
    fees: 'Free \u2014 no fees to save money. High-yield digital bank accounts have no maintaining balance or account fees',
    processingTime: 'Depends on your income and savings rate. At \u20B15,000/month savings: ~12 months for a \u20B160,000 target. At \u20B12,000/month: ~30 months. Start today regardless of the amount',
    tips: [
      'Start with whatever you can \u2014 even \u20B150 or \u20B1100 a day adds up to \u20B11,500-\u20B13,000 a month',
      'The emergency fund is NOT for wants \u2014 it\'s strictly for genuine emergencies: job loss, medical bills, car breakdown, home repairs',
      'Keep it in a liquid, accessible account \u2014 NOT in time deposits, stocks, or investments you can\'t withdraw instantly',
      'In the Filipino context, family obligations are real. Budget for them, but don\'t let them derail your emergency fund completely',
      'Cut unnecessary expenses to boost savings: cook at home instead of food delivery, cancel unused subscriptions, carpool instead of ride-hailing apps',
      'Use the \'pay yourself first\' method \u2014 transfer savings BEFORE you start spending, not after',
      'Don\'t be discouraged by slow progress \u2014 a partial emergency fund is infinitely better than none',
      'Consider the ipon (saving) challenge: save \u20B150 on week 1, \u20B1100 on week 2, \u20B1150 on week 3, etc. By week 52, you\'ll have over \u20B168,000',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'How to Build an Emergency Fund (MoneyMax)', url: 'https://www.moneymax.ph/personal-finance/articles/start-emergency-fund'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'Emergency Fund Guide for Filipinos (Maya)', url: 'https://www.maya.ph/stories/5-best-practices-for-building-an-emergency-fund-a-guide-for-filipinos'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'Emergency Fund Philippines (FinMerkado)', url: 'https://www.finmerkado.ph/post/emergency-fund-philippines-high-interest-savings'),
    ],
  ),
  'understand-payslip': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'understand-payslip',
    title: 'Understand your payslip deductions',
    description: 'Know exactly what SSS, PhilHealth, Pag-IBIG, and withholding tax amounts are being deducted from your salary every month.',
    why: 'Many Filipinos don\'t know what they\'re actually earning vs. what\'s being withheld. Understanding deductions lets you verify your contributions are correct and plan your net take-home budget accurately.',
    how: 'Check your payslip monthly. Verify SSS, PhilHealth, and Pag-IBIG amounts match the official tables. Withholding tax depends on your salary bracket. Use Sandalan\'s Contribution Calculator to verify your employer is computing correctly.',
    priority: 'critical',
    appLink: '/tools/contributions',
    appLinkLabel: 'Calculate Deductions',
    requirements: [
      'Your latest payslip (printed or digital \u2014 ask HR if you don\'t receive one regularly)',
      'Access to the SSS contribution table (2025: 15% total contribution rate, employee share varies by salary bracket)',
      'Access to the PhilHealth premium table (2025: 5% of monthly basic salary, split equally between employer and employee)',
      'Knowledge of Pag-IBIG contribution rates (2% of monthly salary, max \u20B1200/month for employee)',
      'BIR Withholding Tax Table (TRAIN Law graduated rates)',
    ],
    steps: [
      'Step 1: Get your payslip \u2014 request it from HR/payroll if you don\'t automatically receive one. You have a legal right to a payslip under DOLE regulations',
      'Step 2: Identify your Gross Salary \u2014 this is your total salary before any deductions',
      'Step 3: Check SSS deduction \u2014 for 2025, the total contribution rate is 15% (employee share varies). Use the SSS contribution table to verify your deduction matches your Monthly Salary Credit (MSC). MSC ranges from \u20B15,000 to \u20B135,000',
      'Step 4: Check PhilHealth deduction \u2014 the premium rate is 5% of your monthly basic salary, split 50/50 with your employer. Your share is 2.5%. Minimum: \u20B1250/month (your share). Maximum: \u20B12,500/month (for salaries \u20B1100,000+)',
      'Step 5: Check Pag-IBIG deduction \u2014 your employee share is 2% of monthly salary (max compensation basis is \u20B110,000, so max deduction is \u20B1200/month). Your employer matches this amount',
      'Step 6: Check Withholding Tax \u2014 subtract SSS + PhilHealth + Pag-IBIG from your gross salary to get taxable income. Under the TRAIN Law: income up to \u20B120,833/month (\u20B1250,000/year) is tax-exempt. Above that, graduated rates apply (20-35%)',
      'Step 7: Verify Net Pay \u2014 Gross Salary minus (SSS + PhilHealth + Pag-IBIG + Withholding Tax + any voluntary deductions like loans) = your take-home pay',
      'Step 8: Compare your computed amounts with what\'s on your payslip. If there are discrepancies, bring it up with HR/payroll immediately',
      'Step 9: Check your SSS, PhilHealth, and Pag-IBIG portals to confirm your employer is actually remitting the deducted amounts',
    ],
    fees: 'N/A \u2014 these are mandatory deductions, not fees. Your total mandatory deductions typically range from 8-15% of your gross salary depending on your bracket',
    processingTime: 'N/A \u2014 payslip review should be done every payday (semi-monthly or monthly)',
    tips: [
      'Your employer is LEGALLY REQUIRED to give you a payslip. If they refuse, report it to DOLE',
      'Use online calculators like taxcalculatorphilippines.com or sweldongpinoy.com to double-check your deductions',
      'Under the TRAIN Law (2018), if you earn \u20B1250,000 or below annually (about \u20B120,833/month), you are EXEMPT from income tax',
      'Overtime pay, holiday pay, night shift differential, and hazard pay are computed separately and have different tax treatments',
      '13th month pay and other benefits up to \u20B190,000 combined are tax-exempt',
      'If your employer deducts contributions but doesn\'t remit them to SSS/PhilHealth/Pag-IBIG, this is illegal. Check your contribution portals regularly',
      'Keep all your payslips \u2014 they serve as proof of income for loan applications, credit cards, and future employment',
      'Your BIR Form 2316 (issued every January) summarizes your annual income and taxes \u2014 cross-reference it with your total payslip deductions for the year',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'SSS 2025 Contribution Table', url: 'https://www.sss.gov.ph/contribution/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'PhilHealth Premium Contributions', url: 'https://www.philhealth.gov.ph/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'Pag-IBIG Contribution Table', url: 'https://www.pagibigfund.gov.ph/Membership.html'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'BIR Withholding Tax Table (TRAIN Law)', url: 'https://www.bir.gov.ph/tax-information/withholding-tax'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'Sweldong Pinoy Tax Calculator', url: 'https://www.sweldongpinoy.com/'),
    ],
  ),
  'credit-card': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'credit-card',
    title: 'Get a credit card (responsibly)',
    description: 'A credit card builds your credit history, earns rewards/cashback, and provides a safety net \u2014 only if you pay the full balance every month.',
    why: 'Credit cards are a tool, not free money. Paying in full every month costs you nothing (0% effective rate) and earns rewards. Minimum payments trap you in 24\u201336% annual interest \u2014 the single worst financial mistake Filipinos make.',
    how: 'Apply at BPI (Amore), BDO (Visa Classic), or Security Bank (Complete Cashback). Requirements: Certificate of Employment, 2 months payslips, TIN, and 1 valid ID. Start with a low limit. Golden rule: never charge what you can\'t pay by billing date.',
    priority: 'good-to-have',
    requirements: [
      'Must be 21-65 years old (some banks accept 18+ with a co-signer)',
      'Filipino citizen or foreign national residing in the Philippines for at least 2 years',
      'Minimum gross annual income of \u20B1120,000-\u20B1252,000 (varies by bank and card type \u2014 some starter cards accept lower income)',
      'At least 1 year of regular employment or 1-2 years of profitable business/freelance work',
      'Two (2) valid government-issued IDs with photo (passport, driver\'s license, UMID, PhilSys National ID)',
      'TIN (Tax Identification Number)',
      'Certificate of Employment (COE) with compensation \u2014 request from HR',
      'Latest 2-3 months payslips or ITR (Income Tax Return) for self-employed',
      'Proof of billing address (latest utility bill or credit card statement)',
    ],
    steps: [
      'Step 1: Check if you meet the minimum income requirement \u2014 most basic cards require \u20B1120,000-\u20B1180,000 gross annual income (\u20B110,000-\u20B115,000/month)',
      'Step 2: Research starter-friendly credit cards. Top picks for first-timers: PNB Ze-Lo Mastercard (no annual fee, low income requirement), BPI Amore Cashback, RCBC Classic Mastercard, Security Bank Complete Cashback',
      'Step 3: Apply online through the bank\'s website (most convenient) or visit a branch. Online applications: go to the bank\'s official website and look for \'Apply for Credit Card\'',
      'Step 4: Fill out the application form \u2014 provide personal details, employment info, income, and existing bank accounts',
      'Step 5: Upload or submit required documents: valid IDs, COE with salary, latest payslips, proof of billing address',
      'Step 6: Wait for the bank\'s evaluation and credit check (they may call your employer or references to verify)',
      'Step 7: If approved, your credit card will be delivered to your billing address within 7-14 business days',
      'Step 8: Activate your card by calling the activation hotline or through the bank\'s mobile app',
      'Step 9: Set up your online banking to monitor transactions and pay your balance',
      'Step 10: Start with small purchases and ALWAYS pay the full balance before the due date',
    ],
    fees: 'Annual fee: \u20B10-\u20B12,500 depending on the card (some starter cards have no annual fee or waive it for the first year). Late payment fee: \u20B1500-\u20B1850. Interest rate on unpaid balance: 2-3.5% per month (24-42% per year). Over-limit fee: \u20B1500. Cash advance fee: \u20B1200-\u20B1500 + interest from day 1',
    processingTime: 'Application evaluation: 7-14 business days. Card delivery (if approved): 5-10 business days after approval. Total: about 2-4 weeks from application to card in hand',
    tips: [
      'GOLDEN RULE: Pay your FULL balance every month by the due date \u2014 this means you pay ZERO interest. Only paying the minimum traps you in 24-42% annual interest',
      'Start with a low credit limit (\u20B110,000-\u20B130,000) until you develop discipline',
      'Use your credit card for regular expenses you\'d buy anyway (groceries, gas, bills) to earn rewards \u2014 then pay it off in full',
      'NEVER use credit card cash advance \u2014 it charges interest from day 1 with no grace period, plus a transaction fee',
      'Set up auto-pay for the full statement balance to never miss a due date',
      'Keep your credit utilization below 30% of your limit (e.g., don\'t charge more than \u20B19,000 on a \u20B130,000 limit)',
      'If you\'re denied, try secured credit cards (backed by a bank deposit) as a stepping stone \u2014 RCBC and BPI offer these',
      'Having an existing savings/checking account with a bank significantly increases your approval chances for their credit card',
      'Never share your credit card number, CVV, or OTP with anyone \u2014 banks will NEVER ask for these via call, text, or email',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'MoneyMax Credit Cards for First-Timers', url: 'https://www.moneymax.ph/credit-card/articles/credit-cards-for-first-timers'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'How to Apply for Your First Credit Card (MoneyMax)', url: 'https://www.moneymax.ph/credit-card/articles/first-credit-card-guide'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'BSP Consumer Protection', url: 'https://www.bsp.gov.ph/Pages/ConsumerProtection/ConsumerProtection.aspx'),
    ],
  ),

  // ─── Phase 3: Government Contributions ──────────────────────────────────────
  'sss-active': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'sss-active',
    title: 'Verify your SSS contributions are current',
    description: 'Check your SSS contribution history to make sure your employer is remitting your deductions and that your records are accurate.',
    why: 'Some employers deduct SSS but fail to remit \u2014 leaving you with gaps in your contribution history that affect your loan eligibility and eventual pension. You are entitled to sue your employer for this.',
    how: 'Log in to my.sss.gov.ph \u2192 Contributions. Verify each month shows up. If a month is missing and you were employed, file a complaint with SSS. Keep payslip records as proof of your deductions.',
    priority: 'critical',
    appLink: '/tools/contributions',
    appLinkLabel: 'Track Contributions',
    requirements: [
      'Your SSS number (SS number)',
      'A registered My.SSS account at member.sss.gov.ph (if you don\'t have one, register first)',
      'Your My.SSS login credentials (user ID and password)',
      'A computer, tablet, or smartphone with internet access',
      'Your payslips as reference to cross-check deductions vs. actual remittances',
    ],
    steps: [
      'Step 1: Go to member.sss.gov.ph and log in with your My.SSS user ID and password',
      'Step 2: On the dashboard, hover over or click \'E-Services\' in the menu bar',
      'Step 3: In the dropdown menu, select \'Inquiry\' then \'Contributions\'',
      'Step 4: Your contribution history will display \u2014 it shows each month\'s contribution amount, the employer who remitted, and the posting date',
      'Step 5: Cross-reference with your payslips \u2014 for every month you were employed and had SSS deductions, there should be a corresponding entry',
      'Step 6: If a month is MISSING, it means your employer deducted but did not remit \u2014 this is illegal',
      'Step 7: To check employment history: go to E-Services > Inquiry > Employment History to see all employers who reported you',
      'Step 8: If you find discrepancies, file a formal complaint with SSS \u2014 bring your payslips as evidence',
      'Alternative: Download the SSS Mobile App (available on Google Play and App Store) and log in with your My.SSS credentials to check on the go',
    ],
    fees: 'Free \u2014 checking contributions online has no fees',
    processingTime: 'Instant \u2014 contribution records are available immediately upon login. Note: new contributions may take 3-5 working days to post after payment/remittance',
    tips: [
      'Check your contributions at least quarterly \u2014 don\'t wait until you need to file a claim to find out your employer hasn\'t been remitting',
      'Contributions may take 3-5 working days to appear after your employer remits, so don\'t panic if the latest month isn\'t showing yet',
      'Screenshot or download your contribution records periodically as backup documentation',
      'If your employer is not remitting, file a complaint at the nearest SSS branch \u2014 employers who don\'t remit face criminal penalties under RA 11199 (Social Security Act of 2018)',
      'Voluntary members: you can check if your personal payments were posted correctly using the same process',
      'Your total contributions determine your loan eligibility (salary loan requires 36 monthly contributions) and eventual pension amount',
      'If you forgot your My.SSS password, use the \'Forgot Password\' feature \u2014 you\'ll need your SS number and registered email',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'My.SSS Member Portal', url: 'https://member.sss.gov.ph/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'SSS Mobile App', url: 'https://www.sss.gov.ph/download-the-sss-mobile-app-2/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'SSS Official Website', url: 'https://www.sss.gov.ph/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'SSS Hotline', url: 'https://www.sss.gov.ph/contact-us/'),
    ],
  ),
  'philhealth-active': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'philhealth-active',
    title: 'Verify your PhilHealth contributions are current',
    description: 'Check that your employer is remitting your PhilHealth contributions and that your membership is active for hospitalization benefits.',
    why: 'If contributions aren\'t posted, you won\'t be able to use PhilHealth benefits when hospitalized. Members without active contributions may need to pay a differential fee to avail coverage.',
    how: 'Log in to PhilHealth member portal at philhealth.gov.ph \u2192 Contributions. Check for gaps. Your employer should give you an MDR (Member Data Record) confirming active status. For outpatient: present PhilHealth ID and MDR at accredited facilities.',
    priority: 'critical',
    appLink: '/tools/contributions',
    appLinkLabel: 'Track Contributions',
    requirements: [
      'Your PhilHealth Identification Number (PIN)',
      'A registered PhilHealth Member Portal account at memberinquiry.philhealth.gov.ph',
      'Login credentials (PhilHealth number and password)',
      'A computer, tablet, or smartphone with internet access',
      'Your payslips for cross-referencing employer deductions',
    ],
    steps: [
      'Step 1: Go to memberinquiry.philhealth.gov.ph and log in with your PhilHealth number and password',
      'Step 2: If you don\'t have an account yet, click \'Register\' and follow the prompts using your PIN, personal details, and valid email',
      'Step 3: Once logged in, navigate to the Contributions section to view your posted contribution history',
      'Step 4: Verify that each month shows a contribution \u2014 especially if you were employed during that period',
      'Step 5: Check your membership status \u2014 it should show \'Active\' for you to be eligible for hospitalization benefits',
      'Step 6: Cross-reference contributions with your payslip deductions to ensure your employer is remitting correctly',
      'Step 7: If contributions are missing, request your MDR (Member Data Record) from your employer or from a PhilHealth LHIO office',
      'Step 8: Report any discrepancies to PhilHealth by visiting the nearest LHIO or emailing actioncenter@philhealth.gov.ph',
      'Alternative: Email actioncenter@philhealth.gov.ph with your complete name, birthdate, and a photo of your valid ID to request a membership status check',
    ],
    fees: 'Free \u2014 checking PhilHealth status online has no fees',
    processingTime: 'Instant \u2014 records are available upon login. New contributions may take several weeks to post after employer remittance',
    tips: [
      'PhilHealth contributions take longer to post compared to SSS \u2014 don\'t panic if the latest months aren\'t showing yet, but do follow up if it\'s been more than 2 months',
      'Your employer is required to issue your MDR (Member Data Record) \u2014 this is your proof of active membership for hospital admissions',
      'Under the Universal Health Care (UHC) Law, all Filipinos are eligible for PhilHealth benefits, but having active contribution status ensures full benefit coverage',
      'Always present your PhilHealth ID or PhilSys National ID (linked to PhilHealth) at hospital admission \u2014 this triggers the automatic deduction of PhilHealth coverage from your bill',
      'If you\'re changing employers, ensure there\'s no gap in contributions \u2014 the new employer should start remitting immediately',
      'Voluntary members (freelancers, self-employed): you can pay contributions at any accredited payment center or through online banking',
      'Keep your Member Data Record (MDR) accessible \u2014 hospitals require this alongside your PhilHealth ID for benefit claims',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'PhilHealth Member Portal', url: 'https://memberinquiry.philhealth.gov.ph/member/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'PhilHealth Official Website', url: 'https://www.philhealth.gov.ph/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'PhilHealth Online Services', url: 'https://www.philhealth.gov.ph/services/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'PhilHealth Action Center Email', url: 'mailto:actioncenter@philhealth.gov.ph'),
    ],
  ),
  'pagibig-active': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'pagibig-active',
    title: 'Verify your Pag-IBIG contributions are current',
    description: 'Confirm monthly Pag-IBIG deductions are being remitted so your housing loan eligibility and MP2 savings are properly building.',
    why: '24 months of Pag-IBIG contributions makes you eligible for housing loans. If your employer isn\'t remitting, you lose eligibility and your contributions may not count.',
    how: 'Log in at pagibig-fund.gov.ph \u2192 Virtual Pag-IBIG \u2192 Member\'s Contribution History. Or text PAG-IBIG <MID number> to 4643. Contact your HR if months are missing.',
    priority: 'critical',
    appLink: '/tools/contributions',
    appLinkLabel: 'Track Contributions',
    requirements: [
      'Your Pag-IBIG MID (Membership ID) number',
      'A registered Virtual Pag-IBIG account at pagibigfundservices.com/virtualpagibig',
      'Login credentials (registered email and password)',
      'A computer, tablet, or smartphone with internet access',
      'Your payslips for cross-referencing employer deductions',
    ],
    steps: [
      'Step 1: Go to pagibigfundservices.com/virtualpagibig and log in with your registered email and password',
      'Step 2: If you don\'t have an account, click \'Create Account\' and register using your MID number, personal details, and email address',
      'Step 3: Once logged in, click the MENU icon (upper left on desktop, upper right on mobile)',
      'Step 4: Select \'Regular Savings\' (Mandatory Contributions) from the menu',
      'Step 5: View your complete contribution history \u2014 it shows all contributions from your first remittance to the latest, including employee and employer shares',
      'Step 6: Check the total number of contributions, total employee share, total employer share, and accumulated dividends',
      'Step 7: Cross-reference with your payslips \u2014 every month your employer deducted Pag-IBIG should have a corresponding entry',
      'Step 8: If months are missing, contact your HR/payroll department immediately with your payslip evidence',
      'Step 9: To check MP2 savings (if enrolled): go back to the menu and select \'Modified Pag-IBIG II (MP2)\' to see your MP2 contributions and dividends',
      'Alternative: Download the Virtual Pag-IBIG Mobile App from Google Play or App Store for checking on the go',
    ],
    fees: 'Free \u2014 checking contributions online has no fees',
    processingTime: 'Instant \u2014 contribution records are available upon login. New contributions may take a few weeks to post after employer remittance',
    tips: [
      'Check your contributions at least quarterly to catch any non-remittance early',
      'Your total Pag-IBIG savings (employee + employer shares + dividends) can be withdrawn upon retirement, disability, or after 20 years of continuous membership',
      'You need 24 months of contributions to be eligible for Pag-IBIG housing loans and multi-purpose loans',
      'The annual dividend rate has been consistently between 5-7% \u2014 much higher than regular bank savings',
      'Consider enrolling in MP2 (Modified Pag-IBIG II) for voluntary savings that earn the same high dividend rate, tax-free',
      'If your employer is not remitting, report to the nearest Pag-IBIG branch \u2014 penalties apply to non-compliant employers',
      'You can also check your loan balance and loan payment history through Virtual Pag-IBIG',
      'Download statements periodically \u2014 they serve as proof of savings for loan applications',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'Virtual Pag-IBIG Portal', url: 'https://www.pagibigfundservices.com/virtualpagibig/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'Virtual Pag-IBIG Mobile App', url: 'https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=pagibigfund.virtualpagibigapp'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'Pag-IBIG Fund Official Website', url: 'https://www.pagibigfund.gov.ph/'),
    ],
  ),
  '13th-month': ChecklistItem(
    id: '13th-month',
    title: 'Know your 13th month pay rights',
    description: 'All rank-and-file employees are legally entitled to 13th month pay \u2014 at least 1/12 of your basic annual salary, paid on or before December 24.',
    why: 'It\'s not a bonus \u2014 it\'s the law (Presidential Decree No. 851). Up to \u20B190,000 is tax-exempt. Some employers try to include it in monthly salary (\'already included\') which is illegal. Know your rights.',
    how: 'Formula: (Total Basic Salary Earned in a Year) \u00F7 12. Compute yours in Sandalan. If you think you were underpaid, file a complaint with DOLE (Department of Labor and Employment). Must be paid regardless of resignation or separation.',
    priority: 'critical',
    appLink: '/tools/thirteenth-month',
    appLinkLabel: '13th Month Calculator',
    requirements: [
      'Knowledge of your basic monthly salary (excluding overtime, holiday pay, night differential, and allowances unless stated in your contract)',
      'Your payslips for the year to verify total basic salary earned',
      'Employment contract (to check if additional pay components are included in basic salary computation)',
      'DOLE contact information in case of disputes',
    ],
    steps: [
      'Step 1: Understand the formula \u2014 13th Month Pay = Total Basic Salary Earned During the Year \u00F7 12',
      'Step 2: Identify your basic salary \u2014 this is your fixed monthly pay EXCLUDING overtime pay, holiday pay, night shift differential, and allowances (unless your contract says otherwise)',
      'Step 3: If you worked the full year (January-December) with a fixed salary, your 13th month pay equals one month\'s basic salary. Example: \u20B125,000/month x 12 months = \u20B1300,000 \u00F7 12 = \u20B125,000',
      'Step 4: If you worked only part of the year (prorated): multiply your monthly salary by the number of months worked, then divide by 12. Example: Started in July, \u20B125,000/month x 6 months = \u20B1150,000 \u00F7 12 = \u20B112,500',
      'Step 5: Check your payslip or ask HR when the 13th month pay will be released \u2014 it must be paid on or before December 24',
      'Step 6: Verify the amount received matches your computation. If it doesn\'t, request a breakdown from HR',
      'Step 7: If you believe you were underpaid or your employer refuses to pay, file a complaint with DOLE at the nearest regional office',
      'Step 8: Check the tax exemption \u2014 13th month pay and other benefits up to \u20B190,000 combined are tax-exempt. Amounts exceeding \u20B190,000 are subject to income tax',
    ],
    fees: 'N/A \u2014 13th month pay is an employee benefit, not a cost. It is required by law under Presidential Decree No. 851',
    processingTime: 'Must be paid by employer on or before December 24 of each year. Some employers pay half in June and the other half in December',
    tips: [
      '13th month pay is NOT a bonus \u2014 it\'s a mandatory benefit required by law. Your employer cannot skip it or \'include it\' in your monthly salary',
      'ALL rank-and-file employees are entitled to 13th month pay regardless of position, employment status (regular, probationary, contractual), or method of pay (daily, weekly, monthly)',
      'You are entitled to 13th month pay even if you resign or are terminated \u2014 it will be prorated based on months worked',
      'Overtime pay, holiday pay, night shift differential, and hazard pay are NOT included in the computation \u2014 only basic salary',
      'Some generous employers give 14th or 15th month pay as a Christmas bonus \u2014 this is voluntary and separate from the mandatory 13th month',
      'If your employer fails to pay by December 24, no exemption or deferment is allowed. Report non-compliance to DOLE',
      'Managers and supervisors are NOT entitled to 13th month pay under the law, but many companies extend it as a company benefit',
      'The \u20B190,000 tax exemption threshold covers 13th month pay PLUS all other benefits (Christmas bonus, productivity incentives, etc.) \u2014 only the excess is taxed',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'DOLE 13th Month Pay Guidelines', url: 'https://laborlaw.ph/13th-month-pay/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'Presidential Decree No. 851', url: 'https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/1975/12/16/presidential-decree-no-851-s-1975/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'DOLE Official Website', url: 'https://www.dole.gov.ph/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: '13th Month Pay Computation Guide', url: 'https://everythingatwork.com/how-to-compute-13th-month-pay-in-the-philippines-2025-update/'),
    ],
  ),

  // ─── Phase 4: Tax Compliance ────────────────────────────────────────────────
  'bir-2316': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'bir-2316',
    title: 'Get your BIR Form 2316 from your employer',
    description: 'Form 2316 is the Certificate of Compensation Payment and Tax Withheld \u2014 proof of your income and taxes paid, issued by your employer every January.',
    why: 'This document proves your tax was withheld correctly. You need it for loan applications (housing, bank), new employer onboarding, and to verify your annual tax was properly settled. Never lose it.',
    how: 'Ask HR or payroll every January for your 2316 covering the previous year. If your employer failed to issue one, they\'re violating the Tax Code. Scan it and keep a digital copy. Most employers issue it by January 31.',
    priority: 'critical',
    appLink: '/tools/taxes',
    appLinkLabel: 'BIR Tax Tracker',
  ),
  'substituted-filing': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'substituted-filing',
    title: 'Know if you need to file an ITR yourself',
    description: 'Most pure employees with one employer qualify for Substituted Filing \u2014 meaning your employer files on your behalf and you don\'t need to file Form 1700.',
    why: 'Filing when not required wastes time. NOT filing when required leads to penalties of 25% surcharge + 12% interest per year + \u20B11,000 compromise penalty. Know your classification.',
    how: 'You don\'t need to file if: single employer, compensation income only, tax was correctly withheld, employer files BIR Alphalist. You MUST file (Form 1700) if: two or more employers in a year, business income, compensation exceeds \u20B12.4M, or you want a tax refund.',
    priority: 'critical',
    appLink: '/tools/taxes',
    appLinkLabel: 'BIR Tax Tracker',
  ),
  'bir-freelancer': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'bir-freelancer',
    title: 'Register with BIR as freelancer or self-employed',
    description: 'If you have any income outside of a formal employer \u2014 freelancing, consulting, online selling, or a side business \u2014 you must register with BIR.',
    why: 'Unregistered businesses and freelancers face back taxes, 25% surcharge, 12% annual interest, and compromise penalties going back 3\u201310 years. The BIR has been actively running after digital earners and influencers.',
    how: 'File BIR Form 1901 at your RDO with TIN, proof of business address, and valid ID. Register your books of accounts. Print Official Receipts (ORs) or use the eBIRForms system. Annual registration fee: \u20B1500. File quarterly (1701Q) and annual (1701/1701A) ITR.',
    priority: 'critical',
    appLink: '/tools/taxes',
    appLinkLabel: 'BIR Tax Tracker',
  ),
  'bir-deductions': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'bir-deductions',
    title: 'Know your allowable deductions',
    description: 'Self-employed individuals can deduct business expenses OR choose the Optional Standard Deduction (OSD) of 40% of gross income \u2014 whichever lowers your tax more.',
    why: 'Many self-employed Filipinos overpay because they don\'t know they can deduct internet, phone, home office, transportation, professional development, and health insurance premiums from their taxable income.',
    how: 'Keep receipts for all business-related expenses. If expenses exceed 40% of income, itemize. If not, use OSD. Also consider the 8% flat income tax option if gross sales/receipts are below \u20B13,000,000 \u2014 often simpler and lower than graduated rates.',
    priority: 'important',
    appLink: '/tools/taxes',
    appLinkLabel: 'BIR Tax Tracker',
  ),

  // ─── Phase 5: Insurance & Protection ────────────────────────────────────────
  'philhealth-benefits': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'philhealth-benefits',
    title: 'Learn how to actually use your PhilHealth',
    description: 'Knowing how to use your PhilHealth benefits can save you tens of thousands of pesos during hospitalization \u2014 most members don\'t claim what they\'re entitled to.',
    why: 'PhilHealth covers specific amounts per diagnosis (case rate) regardless of actual hospital bill. For normal delivery alone it covers \u20B16,500. Without knowing how to file, you leave money on the table.',
    how: 'Present PhilHealth ID + MDR at accredited hospital admission. The hospital files PhilHealth claims on your behalf. For outpatient: Z-benefits cover cancer, dialysis, and selected conditions. Check philhealth.gov.ph/services for the full benefits table.',
    priority: 'critical',
    appLink: '/tools/insurance',
    appLinkLabel: 'Insurance Tracker',
  ),
  'hmo': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'hmo',
    title: 'Get HMO coverage',
    description: 'An HMO (Health Maintenance Organization) covers outpatient consultations, diagnostics, and emergency room visits that PhilHealth doesn\'t fully cover.',
    why: 'PhilHealth mostly covers inpatient care. A single ER visit, lab workup, or specialist consultation can cost \u20B12,000\u2013\u20B110,000 out of pocket. HMO fills this gap. Company HMO is free \u2014 always enroll in it if offered.',
    how: 'If employed: enroll in your company\'s HMO during open enrollment \u2014 it\'s usually free or subsidized. If self-employed: personal plans from Maxicare, Medicard, or Intellicare start at ~\u20B13,000\u2013\u20B18,000/year. Compare online at HMO comparison sites.',
    priority: 'critical',
    appLink: '/tools/insurance',
    appLinkLabel: 'Insurance Tracker',
  ),
  'life-insurance': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'life-insurance',
    title: 'Get term life insurance',
    description: 'Term life insurance pays your beneficiaries a lump sum if you die during the coverage period \u2014 pure protection with no investment component.',
    why: 'If anyone depends on your income (parents, spouse, kids), you need life insurance. Rule of thumb: 10x your annual income in coverage. Term insurance is 3\u20135x cheaper than VUL for the same coverage. Most Filipinos are oversold VULs when term would serve them better.',
    how: 'Get term insurance first: PRULife\'s PRUTerm One, Sun Life\'s SunTerm, or AXA\'s FlexiProtect. Annual premiums for \u20B11,000,000 coverage start around \u20B13,000\u2013\u20B15,000/year for a healthy 25-year-old. Avoid mixing insurance with investment (VUL) until you fully understand both.',
    priority: 'important',
    appLink: '/tools/insurance',
    appLinkLabel: 'Insurance Tracker',
  ),
  'ctpl': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'ctpl',
    title: 'CTPL: Mandatory vehicle insurance',
    description: 'Compulsory Third Party Liability (CTPL) insurance is required by law for all motor vehicle registrations at LTO. No CTPL = no LTO sticker.',
    why: 'CTPL covers bodily injury or death to third parties in road accidents \u2014 not your own vehicle. It\'s the minimum legal requirement. Driving without valid LTO registration (which requires CTPL) is a criminal offense.',
    how: 'Buy CTPL from any insurance company accredited by LTO: COCOGEN, Malayan, Charter Ping An, etc. 1-year coverage costs ~\u20B1400\u2013\u20B1800. Purchase at LTO during registration renewal, at authorized payment centers, or online through Gcash/Maya.',
    priority: 'important',
    appLink: '/tools/insurance',
    appLinkLabel: 'Insurance Tracker',
  ),

  // ─── Phase 6: Investing & Building Wealth ───────────────────────────────────
  'emergency-fund-6mo': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'emergency-fund-6mo',
    title: 'Build a full 6-month emergency fund',
    description: 'Expand your emergency fund to cover 6 months of living expenses \u2014 especially if you\'re self-employed or in an industry with high job instability.',
    why: '3 months is the minimum. 6 months is the real target \u2014 especially for freelancers, commission-based workers, or those with dependents. This is the foundation; you should not invest until this is done.',
    how: 'Calculate: monthly expenses \u00D7 6. Keep in a separate high-yield savings account (ING, CIMB). Don\'t invest this money \u2014 it must be liquid and immediately accessible. Top it up if you ever tap it.',
    priority: 'critical',
    appLink: '/goals',
    appLinkLabel: 'Set Goal',
  ),
  'mp2': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'mp2',
    title: 'Start Pag-IBIG MP2 savings',
    description: 'Modified Pag-IBIG II is a voluntary savings program that earns 6\u20137% annual dividends, fully tax-free \u2014 one of the best guaranteed returns in the Philippines.',
    why: 'MP2 consistently outperforms most bank time deposits and UITFs with much lower risk. It\'s government-guaranteed. The 5-year maturity is flexible \u2014 you can withdraw dividends annually or let them compound.',
    how: 'Log in to Virtual Pag-IBIG \u2192 MP2 Enrollment. Minimum: \u20B1500/month or lump sum \u20B1500. Set up auto-debit from your bank account. After 5 years, you can withdraw the entire principal + dividends or roll over for another 5 years.',
    priority: 'important',
    appLink: '/goals',
    appLinkLabel: 'Track Savings Goal',
  ),
  'uitf': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'uitf',
    title: 'Open a UITF or mutual fund account',
    description: 'Unit Investment Trust Funds (UITFs) pool money from many investors to invest in bonds, equities, or a mix \u2014 professionally managed with as little as \u20B11,000.',
    why: 'Higher long-term returns than savings accounts (equity UITFs historically return 8\u201312% annually). You can start small, invest regularly, and not need to pick individual stocks. Good for 5\u201310+ year goals.',
    how: 'Open through your existing bank: BDO, BPI, or UnionBank UITFs can be started online. Choose based on risk: Money Market (lowest) \u2192 Bond \u2192 Balanced \u2192 Equity (highest). Start with \u20B11,000. Read the Key Information Document (KID) before investing.',
    priority: 'important',
    appLink: '/goals',
    appLinkLabel: 'Track Investment Goal',
  ),
  'stocks-pse': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'stocks-pse',
    title: 'Learn about the Philippine Stock Exchange',
    description: 'Investing in PSE-listed companies lets you own a piece of SM, Ayala, JG Summit, BDO, and others \u2014 with the potential for long-term wealth creation.',
    why: 'The PSE has historically returned 8\u201312% annually over 10+ year periods. Dividends provide passive income. Owning blue-chip stocks is a proven long-term wealth strategy \u2014 but requires patience and a 10+ year mindset.',
    how: 'Open an account with COL Financial (easiest for beginners), BDO Nomura, or First Metro Securities. Minimum: \u20B11,000 with COL. Start with blue-chip stocks: SM, Ayala Land, BDO, BPI, Jollibee. Never invest money you need within 5 years.',
    priority: 'good-to-have',
    appLink: '/goals',
    appLinkLabel: 'Track Investment Goal',
  ),
  'sss-voluntary': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'sss-voluntary',
    title: 'Make voluntary SSS contributions to increase your pension',
    description: 'The maximum monthly SSS pension is tied to your Monthly Salary Credit (MSC). Higher contributions = higher pension. You can voluntarily contribute above the minimum.',
    why: 'The default SSS pension for minimum-wage workers can be as low as \u20B11,500\u2013\u20B12,000/month \u2014 far below the poverty line. Increasing your MSC now dramatically increases your future retirement pension.',
    how: 'Log in to my.sss.gov.ph \u2192 Payment Reference Number (PRN) \u2192 select voluntary contribution amount. You can contribute up to the maximum MSC of \u20B130,000. Payments via GCash, online banking, or SSS-accredited payment centers.',
    priority: 'good-to-have',
    appLink: '/tools/contributions',
    appLinkLabel: 'Contributions Tracker',
  ),

  // ─── Phase 7: Estate & Legacy Planning ──────────────────────────────────────
  'beneficiaries': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'beneficiaries',
    title: 'Update beneficiaries on all accounts',
    description: 'Make sure your SSS, PhilHealth, Pag-IBIG, bank accounts, and insurance policies have updated and correct beneficiaries.',
    why: 'Without designated beneficiaries, death benefits get tied up in lengthy legal proceedings. Courts, lawyers, and estate taxes can eat up to 20\u201330% of what you leave behind. A simple form update can save your family years of grief.',
    how: 'SSS: Update E-4 form at any SSS branch. Pag-IBIG: Submit MDF (Membership Data Form) at a branch. Banks: Ask for beneficiary designation forms \u2014 most banks offer this. Insurance: Call your insurance provider or go to their office.',
    priority: 'important',
  ),
  'will': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'will',
    title: 'Create a basic last will and testament',
    description: 'A notarized will ensures your assets go where you want them to, protects your family from succession disputes, and makes the estate settlement process faster.',
    why: 'Without a will, Philippine intestate law distributes your estate according to the Civil Code \u2014 which may not match your wishes. Family disputes over inheritance are common and devastating. A will minimizes conflict.',
    how: 'Hire a lawyer to draft a notarial will (most affordable: \u20B13,000\u2013\u20B18,000 with a notary). Alternatively, a holographic will (handwritten, dated, signed) is valid in the Philippines with no notarization needed. Keep the original in a safe place; give a copy to a trusted person.',
    priority: 'good-to-have',
  ),
  'estate-tax': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'estate-tax',
    title: 'Understand estate tax',
    description: 'When you pass away, the Philippine government imposes a 6% estate tax on the net estate above \u20B15,000,000 \u2014 paid before heirs can claim assets.',
    why: 'Many Filipino families lose portions of their inheritance because they don\'t understand estate taxes or can\'t afford to pay them. Prior planning (insurance, proper titling, estate tax amnesty) can significantly reduce this burden.',
    how: 'The estate tax return (BIR Form 1801) must be filed within 1 year of death. Consider estate tax insurance \u2014 a life insurance policy sized to cover anticipated estate taxes. Keep property titles, bank records, and key documents organized and accessible to heirs.',
    priority: 'good-to-have',
  ),

  // ─── Phase 5b: Tahanan (additional) ─────────────────────────────────────────
  'hmo-coverage': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'hmo-coverage',
    title: 'Get HMO coverage',
    description: 'An HMO covers outpatient consultations, diagnostic tests, emergency room visits, and dental care that PhilHealth doesn\'t fully handle.',
    why: 'PhilHealth primarily covers inpatient hospitalization through case rates. A single ER visit or specialist consultation can cost ₱3,000–₱10,000. With a family, medical expenses multiply quickly. HMO fills the gap between PhilHealth and out-of-pocket costs.',
    how: 'If employed, enroll in your company\'s HMO during open enrollment (usually free or subsidized). If self-employed, compare personal plans from Maxicare, Medicard, Intellicare, or Cocolife. Family plans start at ₱15,000–₱30,000/year depending on coverage and age.',
    priority: 'important',
    appLink: '/tools/insurance',
    appLinkLabel: 'Insurance Tracker',
    requirements: [
      'Valid government-issued ID',
      'For company HMO: employment confirmation and enrollment form from HR',
      'For personal HMO: application form, medical history declaration',
      'Recent medical exam results (some providers require this for ages 45+)',
    ],
    steps: [
      'If employed: Ask HR about the company HMO provider and enrollment dates. Enroll yourself, spouse, and dependents',
      'If self-employed: Research providers — Maxicare, Medicard, Intellicare, and Cocolife are the major ones. Compare coverage, network of hospitals, and premiums',
      'Choose a plan tier based on your family\'s needs: basic (outpatient + ER), standard (adds hospitalization), or comprehensive (adds dental, maternity, wellness)',
      'Fill out the application form and declare pre-existing conditions honestly (non-disclosure can void your coverage)',
      'Pay the annual or quarterly premium',
      'Receive your HMO card and familiarize yourself with accredited hospitals and clinics near your home and workplace',
    ],
    fees: 'Company HMO: usually free. Personal plans: ₱3,000–₱8,000/year (individual), ₱15,000–₱30,000/year (family)',
    processingTime: 'Company HMO: immediate upon enrollment. Personal: 3-7 business days for card issuance',
    tips: [
      'Always check if your preferred hospital or clinic is in the HMO\'s accredited network before enrolling',
      'Don\'t skip the dental benefit — a single root canal costs ₱5,000–₱15,000 without coverage',
      'Keep your HMO card with you at all times — ER visits are covered even at night and on weekends',
      'Review your plan annually and upgrade if your family\'s needs change',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'Maxicare', url: 'https://www.maxicare.com.ph/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'Medicard', url: 'https://www.medicard.com.ph/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'Intellicare', url: 'https://www.intellicare.com.ph/'),
    ],
  ),
  'joint-budget': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'joint-budget',
    title: 'Create a joint budget with partner',
    description: 'A shared budget system prevents the #1 cause of marital conflict — money disagreements — and ensures you\'re building wealth as a team.',
    why: 'Money is consistently the top cause of marital stress in the Philippines. Without a shared system, one partner may be saving while the other is spending. A joint budget creates transparency, shared goals, and accountability.',
    how: 'Use the "yours, mine, ours" three-account system: each partner has a personal account for individual spending, and a joint account for shared expenses (rent, bills, groceries, savings). Agree on a fixed percentage or amount each contributes to the joint account.',
    priority: 'important',
    appLink: '/budgets',
    appLinkLabel: 'Set Up Budget',
    requirements: [
      'Full financial disclosure from both partners (income, debts, obligations)',
      'Agreement on shared financial goals (home, children, retirement)',
      'A joint bank account for shared expenses',
      'Individual bank accounts for personal spending (optional but recommended)',
    ],
    steps: [
      'Have the "money talk" — share your full financial picture: income, debts, family support obligations, savings, and financial goals',
      'List all shared monthly expenses: rent/mortgage, utilities, groceries, transportation, insurance, children\'s expenses',
      'Decide on the contribution method: equal split, proportional to income (if one earns more), or full pooling',
      'Open a joint bank account for shared expenses. Both partners should have access and visibility',
      'Set up the budget in Sandalan — create categories for shared expenses and track spending together',
      'Schedule a monthly "money date" to review spending, adjust the budget, and discuss upcoming expenses',
      'Agree on a spending threshold — purchases above ₱X require discussion with your partner',
    ],
    tips: [
      'The proportional method is fairest: if Partner A earns 60% of household income, they contribute 60% to joint expenses',
      'Keep personal spending accounts — everyone needs some financial autonomy',
      'Don\'t hide purchases or debts. Financial infidelity erodes trust faster than overspending',
      'Revisit the budget after major life changes: new baby, job change, salary increase',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'Sandalan Budget Tool', url: '/budgets'),
    ],
  ),
  'child-savings': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'child-savings',
    title: 'Set up child\'s savings account',
    description: 'Starting a savings or investment account for your child early takes advantage of compound interest — even small amounts grow significantly over 18 years.',
    why: 'Private university tuition rises 8–12% annually. A ₱2,000/month investment starting at birth, earning 7% annually, grows to approximately ₱870,000 by age 18. Starting when they\'re 10 would give you only ₱280,000 with the same contribution. Time is the most powerful factor.',
    how: 'Open a minor\'s savings account at any major bank (BDO, BPI, Metrobank, UnionBank). Most require a maintaining balance of ₱100–₱500. For longer-term growth, consider Pag-IBIG MP2 in your name earmarked for education, or a UITF through your bank app.',
    priority: 'good-to-have',
    appLink: '/goals',
    appLinkLabel: 'Set Education Fund Goal',
    requirements: [
      'Child\'s PSA birth certificate',
      'Parent/guardian\'s valid government ID',
      'Initial deposit (₱100–₱500 depending on bank)',
      'TIN of parent/guardian',
    ],
    steps: [
      'Choose the right account type: minor\'s savings account (bank), UITF in your name (for higher returns), or Pag-IBIG MP2 (tax-free, 6-7% returns)',
      'For a bank savings account: Visit any major bank branch with the child\'s birth certificate and your ID. Minimum deposit is usually ₱100–₱500',
      'Set up automatic transfers — even ₱1,000–₱2,000/month makes a huge difference over time',
      'For higher returns: Open a UITF (balanced or equity fund) through your bank app. Start with ₱1,000 and add monthly',
      'Track the goal in Sandalan — set the target amount based on projected education costs',
      'Increase the monthly contribution whenever your income grows — aim to match tuition inflation (8-12%/year)',
    ],
    tips: [
      'Don\'t put education funds in a regular savings account (1-2% interest doesn\'t beat inflation)',
      'For 15+ year timelines, equity UITFs or index funds historically outperform all other options',
      'Pag-IBIG MP2 is excellent for education savings: 6-7% tax-free, government-guaranteed',
      'Avoid "education plans" from insurance companies — high fees and low returns compared to direct investing',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'BPI Kids Savings', url: 'https://www.bpi.com.ph/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'BDO Junior Savers', url: 'https://www.bdo.com.ph/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'Pag-IBIG MP2 Program', url: 'https://www.pagibigfund.gov.ph/'),
    ],
  ),
  'update-beneficiaries': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'update-beneficiaries',
    title: 'Review and update beneficiaries',
    description: 'Life changes — marriage, children, separation — mean your beneficiary designations may be outdated. Wrong beneficiaries can cause legal nightmares for your family.',
    why: 'If your SSS beneficiary is still your parent but you\'re now married with children, the death benefit may go to the wrong person or get tied up in legal disputes. Updating beneficiaries is free and takes 30 minutes but can save your family months of legal trouble.',
    how: 'Review and update beneficiaries on ALL financial accounts: SSS (Form E-4), Pag-IBIG (MDF), PhilHealth (PMRF), bank accounts, insurance policies, and investments. Do this annually or after any major life event.',
    priority: 'important',
    requirements: [
      'Current beneficiary records from each institution',
      'Valid government ID',
      'Marriage certificate or birth certificates of children (if applicable)',
      'Updated forms: SSS Form E-4, Pag-IBIG MDF, PhilHealth PMRF',
    ],
    steps: [
      'List all accounts with beneficiary designations: SSS, Pag-IBIG, PhilHealth, bank accounts (savings, checking, time deposits), insurance policies, UITFs/investments',
      'Check current beneficiaries on each account — log in online or request records at the branch',
      'Identify accounts with outdated beneficiaries (e.g., still listing parents when you have a spouse/children)',
      'SSS: Download Form E-4 from sss.gov.ph, fill out with updated beneficiaries, submit at any SSS branch',
      'Pag-IBIG: Submit updated MDF (Membership Data Form) at any Pag-IBIG branch or through Virtual Pag-IBIG',
      'PhilHealth: Update PMRF (PhilHealth Member Registration Form) at any PhilHealth office',
      'Banks: Visit each bank and request the beneficiary designation form. Some banks allow online updates',
      'Insurance: Contact your insurance agent or company to update the beneficiary designation',
    ],
    fees: 'Free — all beneficiary updates are free of charge',
    processingTime: 'Same day for most institutions. Insurance may take 1-2 weeks',
    tips: [
      'Set a calendar reminder to review beneficiaries every year (January is a good time)',
      'After marriage, update ALL accounts within the first month — don\'t wait',
      'Keep a master list of all accounts and their designated beneficiaries in a secure but accessible place',
      'For insurance: irrevocable beneficiary designations offer estate tax advantages but cannot be changed without the beneficiary\'s consent',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'SSS Member Portal', url: 'https://member.sss.gov.ph/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'Virtual Pag-IBIG', url: 'https://www.pagibigfundservices.com/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'PhilHealth Member Portal', url: 'https://memberinquiry.philhealth.gov.ph/'),
    ],
  ),
  'comprehensive-car-insurance': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'comprehensive-car-insurance',
    title: 'Get comprehensive car insurance',
    description: 'Comprehensive car insurance covers theft, accident damage, fire, flood, and third-party liability — far beyond the minimum CTPL requirement.',
    why: 'CTPL only covers third-party bodily injury. If your car is stolen, flooded, or totaled in an accident, CTPL pays nothing for YOUR vehicle. A single car theft or flood event can cost you ₱300,000–₱1,000,000. Comprehensive insurance is the financial safety net.',
    how: 'Compare quotes from major insurers: Malayan, Charter Ping An, Standard Insurance, FPG, COCOGEN. You can get quotes online or through insurance brokers. Annual premium is typically 2-4% of vehicle value. Consider adding Acts of Nature (AON) coverage for typhoons and floods.',
    priority: 'good-to-have',
    appLink: '/tools/insurance',
    appLinkLabel: 'Insurance Tracker',
    requirements: [
      'Vehicle OR/CR (Official Receipt and Certificate of Registration)',
      'Valid driver\'s license',
      'Vehicle photos (most insurers require 4-6 angles)',
      'Vehicle inspection (some insurers require this for secondhand vehicles)',
    ],
    steps: [
      'Determine your vehicle\'s current fair market value (FMV) — this determines the coverage amount and premium',
      'Get quotes from at least 3 insurance companies — compare coverage, exclusions, deductibles, and premiums',
      'Choose your coverage package: basic comprehensive (theft + own damage + TPL) or comprehensive with add-ons (AON, personal accident, roadside assistance)',
      'Submit requirements: OR/CR, driver\'s license, vehicle photos, application form',
      'Pay the annual premium. Most insurers offer installment payment (quarterly or semi-annual)',
      'Receive your policy document and insurance certificate. Keep a copy in your vehicle at all times',
      'Note the claims hotline number in your phone — you\'ll need it if you have an accident',
    ],
    fees: 'Annual premium: typically 2-4% of vehicle value. For a ₱800,000 car: ₱16,000–₱32,000/year. Deductible per claim: ₱2,000–₱5,000',
    processingTime: 'Policy issuance: 1-3 business days. Claims processing: 5-15 business days',
    tips: [
      'Always add Acts of Nature (AON) coverage — typhoons and floods are frequent in the Philippines',
      'Higher deductible = lower premium. If you can afford to absorb ₱5,000 per claim, opt for the higher deductible to save on premiums',
      'Install a dashcam — it helps in claims disputes and some insurers offer a premium discount',
      'Report accidents to your insurer within 24 hours. Late reporting can void your claim',
      'Check if your insurer has accredited repair shops (casa partner) near your area',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'Insurance Commission', url: 'https://www.insurance.gov.ph/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'Malayan Insurance', url: 'https://www.malayan.com.ph/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'Charter Ping An', url: 'https://www.charterpingan.com/'),
    ],
  ),

  // ─── Phase 6b: Tugatog (additional) ────────────────────────────────────────
  'open-brokerage': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'open-brokerage',
    title: 'Open a stock brokerage account',
    description: 'A brokerage account gives you access to buy and sell stocks on the Philippine Stock Exchange — your gateway to equity investing and long-term wealth building.',
    why: 'The PSE has historically returned 8–12% annually over 10+ year periods. Owning blue-chip stocks or FMETF (the PSE index ETF) is one of the most accessible ways to build long-term wealth. You can start with as little as ₱1,000.',
    how: 'Open an account with an online broker. COL Financial is the most beginner-friendly (minimum ₱1,000). BDO Nomura and First Metro Securities are good alternatives. Apply online — most accounts are approved within 1-3 business days.',
    priority: 'good-to-have',
    appLink: '/goals',
    appLinkLabel: 'Track Investment Goal',
    requirements: [
      'Two valid government-issued IDs',
      'Proof of income (payslip, ITR, or bank statement)',
      'TIN (Tax Identification Number)',
      'Bank account for fund transfers',
      'Completed application form (online for COL Financial)',
    ],
    steps: [
      'Choose your broker: COL Financial (easiest, ₱1,000 minimum), BDO Nomura (₱25,000 minimum), First Metro Securities (₱25,000 minimum), or PhilStocks (₱5,000 minimum)',
      'Visit the broker\'s website and complete the online application form',
      'Upload required documents: IDs, proof of income, signature specimen',
      'Wait for account approval (1-3 business days for online applications)',
      'Fund your account via bank transfer, GCash, or over-the-counter deposit',
      'Familiarize yourself with the trading platform — most brokers offer tutorials and demo modes',
      'Start with blue-chip stocks or FMETF — don\'t jump into speculative stocks as a beginner',
    ],
    fees: 'Account opening: Free. Trading fees: ~1.2% round trip (commission + VAT + PSE fees + stock transaction tax). No annual maintenance fees for most online brokers',
    processingTime: '1-3 business days for account approval. Fund transfers: same day to 1 business day',
    tips: [
      'Start with FMETF if you don\'t want to pick individual stocks — it\'s like buying all 30 PSEi companies at once',
      'Never invest money you\'ll need within 5 years — stocks are volatile in the short term',
      'Use peso-cost averaging: invest a fixed amount monthly regardless of market conditions',
      'Read the broker\'s research reports — they\'re free and help you understand company fundamentals',
      'Avoid penny stocks and "hot tips" from social media — stick to established blue chips',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'COL Financial', url: 'https://www.colfinancial.com/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'BDO Nomura', url: 'https://www.bdonomura.com/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'PSE (Philippine Stock Exchange)', url: 'https://www.pse.com.ph/'),
    ],
  ),
  'invest-mp2': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'invest-mp2',
    title: 'Invest in Pag-IBIG MP2',
    description: 'Pag-IBIG MP2 (Modified Pag-IBIG II) is a voluntary savings program offering 6-7% annual dividends — tax-free and government-guaranteed.',
    why: 'MP2 consistently delivers the highest risk-adjusted returns among safe investments in the Philippines. At 6-7% tax-free, it beats bank time deposits (3-5%), most bond funds, and even some UITFs. It\'s government-guaranteed and has a simple 5-year term.',
    how: 'Enroll through Virtual Pag-IBIG (pagibigfundservices.com). Minimum contribution: ₱500. Set up auto-debit from your bank account for monthly contributions. After 5 years, choose to withdraw or roll over for another 5 years.',
    priority: 'important',
    appLink: '/goals',
    appLinkLabel: 'Track MP2 Goal',
    requirements: [
      'Active Pag-IBIG membership (at least 1 monthly contribution)',
      'Pag-IBIG MID number',
      'Virtual Pag-IBIG account (register at pagibigfundservices.com)',
      'Bank account or GCash/Maya for contributions',
    ],
    steps: [
      'Log in to Virtual Pag-IBIG at pagibigfundservices.com',
      'Go to MP2 Enrollment and submit the application',
      'Choose your contribution method: lump sum, monthly auto-debit, or manual payment',
      'Make your first contribution: minimum ₱500 (lump sum or monthly)',
      'Set up auto-debit from your bank account for hassle-free monthly contributions',
      'Track your MP2 savings balance through Virtual Pag-IBIG',
      'After 5 years: withdraw the full amount (principal + accumulated dividends) or roll over for another 5 years',
    ],
    fees: 'No fees. All contributions earn dividends. No penalties for minimum contributions',
    processingTime: 'Enrollment: instant online. Contributions posted: 1-3 business days. Maturity withdrawal: 5-10 business days',
    tips: [
      'You can open multiple MP2 accounts and stagger them — one maturing every year for regular access to funds',
      'MP2 dividends are tax-free under current tax law — a significant advantage over taxable investments',
      'Increase your contributions when you get a raise — MP2 has no maximum contribution limit',
      'Consider using MP2 as your medium-term savings vehicle (education fund, house down payment) alongside higher-risk investments',
      'Dividends are declared annually (usually February) — check Virtual Pag-IBIG for your updated balance',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'Virtual Pag-IBIG', url: 'https://www.pagibigfundservices.com/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'Pag-IBIG Fund MP2 Program', url: 'https://www.pagibigfund.gov.ph/'),
    ],
  ),
  'start-uitf-mutual': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'start-uitf-mutual',
    title: 'Start UITF or mutual fund',
    description: 'Unit Investment Trust Funds (UITFs) and mutual funds provide professionally managed, diversified investments starting at ₱1,000 — perfect for building wealth without picking individual stocks.',
    why: 'UITFs and mutual funds give you exposure to a diversified portfolio managed by professionals. Equity UITFs historically return 8-12% annually over 10+ year periods. They\'re easier than stock picking and more liquid than real estate or MP2.',
    how: 'Open a UITF through your existing bank app (BDO, BPI, UnionBank, Metrobank). Choose based on your risk tolerance: Money Market (safest) → Bond → Balanced → Equity (highest growth). Start with ₱1,000 and add monthly.',
    priority: 'good-to-have',
    appLink: '/goals',
    appLinkLabel: 'Track Investment Goal',
    requirements: [
      'Existing bank account with a UITF-offering bank (BDO, BPI, UnionBank, Metrobank, etc.)',
      'Valid government ID',
      'Completed client suitability assessment (online quiz about your risk tolerance)',
      'Initial investment: ₱1,000–₱10,000 depending on the fund',
    ],
    steps: [
      'Log in to your bank\'s online platform or mobile app',
      'Navigate to the investment/UITF section',
      'Complete the Client Suitability Assessment — this determines which funds match your risk profile',
      'Choose a fund type: Money Market (low risk, 2-4%), Bond (low-medium, 4-7%), Balanced (medium, 6-9%), or Equity (higher risk, 8-12% long-term)',
      'Read the Key Information Document (KID) and UITF Declaration of Trust',
      'Make your initial investment (minimum ₱1,000 for most funds)',
      'Set up automatic monthly subscription (UITF auto-invest) for peso-cost averaging',
    ],
    fees: 'Management fee: 0.5-2% annually (deducted from NAV). Entry/exit fees: 0-2% depending on the fund. No transaction fees for most bank UITFs',
    processingTime: 'Account opening: instant (if you have a bank account). Subscription: 1-2 business days. Redemption: 2-4 business days',
    tips: [
      'For 10+ year goals, equity UITFs provide the best returns despite short-term volatility',
      'Peso-cost averaging (investing a fixed amount monthly) reduces the impact of market timing',
      'Compare UITFs from different banks — management fees and performance vary significantly',
      'Don\'t panic-sell during market dips. Historically, the market always recovers over 5-10 year periods',
      'Check NAVPU (Net Asset Value Per Unit) monthly — your bank app shows this',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'BPI UITF', url: 'https://www.bpiassetmanagement.com/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'BDO UITF', url: 'https://www.bdo.com.ph/trust-and-investments/uitf'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'BSP UITF Directory', url: 'https://www.bsp.gov.ph/'),
    ],
  ),
  'increase-life-insurance': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'increase-life-insurance',
    title: 'Increase life insurance coverage',
    description: 'As your responsibilities grow — mortgage, children, spouse — your life insurance coverage should grow too. The coverage you got at 25 may be grossly inadequate at 40.',
    why: 'Life insurance should cover 10x your annual income or enough to replace your income for the years your dependents need it. A ₱1,000,000 policy bought at 25 doesn\'t cover a ₱3,000,000 mortgage, ₱2,000,000 in education costs, and 15 years of family expenses.',
    how: 'Review your current coverage and compare it to the "10x annual income" rule or the detailed needs analysis. If underinsured, add a new term policy or increase your existing coverage. Term insurance is the most cost-effective way to add coverage.',
    priority: 'important',
    appLink: '/tools/insurance',
    appLinkLabel: 'Insurance Tracker',
    requirements: [
      'Current insurance policy documents',
      'Recent medical exam results (required for policies above ₱2-3M coverage)',
      'Income documentation (for underwriting)',
      'Valid government ID',
    ],
    steps: [
      'Calculate your insurance need: (annual family expenses × years until youngest child is independent) + outstanding debts + education fund − current savings and investments',
      'Check your current life insurance coverage amount and compare to your calculated need',
      'If underinsured: contact your insurance agent or compare term life quotes online',
      'Get quotes for additional term coverage: PRULife, Sun Life, AXA, Manulife, and FWD all offer online quotes',
      'Consider a 15-20 year term to match your remaining working years and child-rearing period',
      'Complete the medical exam (if required) and submit the application',
      'Update your beneficiary designations on the new policy',
    ],
    fees: 'Term life insurance at age 40: approximately ₱8,000–₱20,000/year for ₱5,000,000 coverage (varies by health, smoking status, and insurer)',
    processingTime: 'Application to policy issuance: 1-4 weeks (depends on medical exam scheduling and underwriting)',
    tips: [
      'Term insurance is 3-5x cheaper than VUL for the same death benefit — buy term and invest the difference',
      'Non-smokers get significantly lower premiums — if you quit smoking for 12 months, most insurers reclassify you',
      'Get insured before any health diagnosis — pre-existing conditions can lead to exclusions or higher premiums',
      'Compare quotes from at least 3 insurers — premiums vary by 20-40% for the same coverage',
      'Consider adding a critical illness rider for an extra ₱2,000–₱5,000/year',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'Insurance Commission', url: 'https://www.insurance.gov.ph/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'Sun Life Philippines', url: 'https://www.sunlife.com.ph/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'PRU Life UK', url: 'https://www.prulifeuk.com.ph/'),
    ],
  ),
  'create-will': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'create-will',
    title: 'Create a will',
    description: 'A last will and testament ensures your assets go where you want them to and prevents devastating family disputes over inheritance.',
    why: 'Without a will, Philippine intestate law distributes your estate according to rigid rules that may not match your wishes. Family disputes over inheritance are common and can last years, costing tens of thousands in legal fees. A simple will prevents all of this.',
    how: 'You have two options: (1) Notarial will — typed, signed by you and 3 witnesses, notarized by a lawyer. Cost: ₱3,000–₱8,000. Strongest legal standing. (2) Holographic will — entirely handwritten by you, dated, and signed. Free. Legally valid but easier to contest.',
    priority: 'important',
    requirements: [
      'Complete inventory of your assets (properties, bank accounts, investments, vehicles, valuable personal property)',
      'List of your intended beneficiaries and their shares',
      'For notarial will: a lawyer and 3 witnesses (not beneficiaries)',
      'For holographic will: pen and paper (must be entirely in your handwriting)',
    ],
    steps: [
      'Create an inventory of all your assets: real property (with TCT/CCT numbers), bank accounts, investments, insurance policies, vehicles, and valuable personal property',
      'Determine your intended distribution, keeping in mind the forced heirship rules (legitimes) under Philippine law',
      'For a notarial will: engage a lawyer (₱3,000–₱8,000). The lawyer drafts the will, you sign it with 3 witnesses, and the lawyer notarizes it',
      'For a holographic will: write the entire will by hand (typed or printed is NOT valid), date it, and sign every page',
      'Store the original in a secure location: fireproof safe, safety deposit box, or with your lawyer',
      'Give a copy to your spouse or a trusted family member — they need to know the will exists and where to find it',
      'Review and update the will every 2-3 years or after major life events (birth of child, property purchase, marriage/separation)',
    ],
    fees: 'Holographic will: Free. Notarial will: ₱3,000–₱8,000 (lawyer\'s fee + notarization). Probate (after death): ₱20,000–₱100,000+ depending on estate complexity',
    processingTime: 'Holographic will: 30 minutes. Notarial will: 1-2 weeks (drafting + signing ceremony)',
    tips: [
      'A holographic will is better than no will — you can write one tonight in 30 minutes',
      'Under Philippine law, you cannot disinherit compulsory heirs (legitimate children, spouse, parents) from their "legitime" — only the "free portion" can be distributed at your discretion',
      'Keep the will updated — an outdated will can be as problematic as no will at all',
      'Do NOT store your only copy of the will in a safety deposit box — banks freeze these upon death, making access difficult',
      'Tell at least 2 people that your will exists and where it\'s stored',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'Civil Code on Succession', url: 'https://www.lawphil.net/statutes/repacts/ra1949/ra_386_1949.html'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'IBP (Integrated Bar of the Philippines)', url: 'https://www.ibp.ph/'),
    ],
  ),

  // ─── Phase 7b: Paghahanda (additional) ──────────────────────────────────────
  'compute-retirement-number': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'compute-retirement-number',
    title: 'Compute your retirement number',
    description: 'Your "retirement number" is the total savings you need to retire comfortably. Without knowing this number, retirement planning is just guessing.',
    why: 'Most Filipinos have no idea how much they need to retire. The default assumption — "my SSS pension will be enough" — is dangerously wrong. The average SSS pension is ₱6,000–₱12,000/month, far below what most families need. Knowing your number lets you plan and close the gap.',
    how: 'Use the 25x rule: multiply your desired annual retirement expenses by 25. Then subtract your expected SSS pension (annualized) and other guaranteed income. The gap is what you need to save. Use Sandalan\'s Retirement Projection tool for a personalized computation.',
    priority: 'critical',
    appLink: '/tools/retirement',
    appLinkLabel: 'Retirement Projection',
    requirements: [
      'Your current monthly expenses (use your Sandalan budget data)',
      'Your SSS contribution history (check at my.sss.gov.ph)',
      'Current savings and investment balances',
      'Expected retirement age',
    ],
    steps: [
      'Calculate your desired monthly retirement income: typically 70-80% of your current expenses (some costs decrease in retirement, others increase)',
      'Multiply by 12 to get annual retirement income needed',
      'Apply the 25x rule: annual income × 25 = your retirement number',
      'Check your SSS contribution history and estimate your monthly pension using the SSS formula',
      'Subtract your expected annual SSS pension (× 12 months × 25) from your retirement number — this is the gap your savings must fill',
      'Calculate how much you need to save monthly to close the gap by your target retirement age',
      'Use the Retirement Projection tool in Sandalan for a detailed, personalized computation',
    ],
    tips: [
      'Be conservative — use 30x instead of 25x if you want extra safety margin',
      'Don\'t forget healthcare costs — these accelerate after 60 and can consume 30-40% of retirement expenses',
      'Review and recalculate your retirement number every year — expenses, inflation, and investment returns change',
      'If your number feels impossibly large, remember: you have time, compound interest, and the ability to adjust your lifestyle',
      'Consider part-time work or passive income in early retirement to supplement savings',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'SSS Member Portal', url: 'https://member.sss.gov.ph/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'Sandalan Retirement Tool', url: '/tools/retirement'),
    ],
  ),
  'maximize-sss-contributions': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'maximize-sss-contributions',
    title: 'Maximize SSS contributions',
    description: 'Contributing at the highest Monthly Salary Credit (MSC) bracket significantly increases your future SSS pension — potentially doubling or tripling it.',
    why: 'The SSS pension formula directly uses your Average Monthly Salary Credit. Contributing at MSC ₱30,000 vs MSC ₱10,000 can mean the difference between a ₱5,000/month pension and a ₱15,000/month pension. Every peso you contribute now pays dividends for the rest of your retirement life.',
    how: 'If employed, ask HR to ensure your contribution is based on your actual salary (some employers contribute at the minimum to save costs — this is illegal). If self-employed or voluntary, increase your contribution amount through My.SSS to the maximum MSC bracket.',
    priority: 'critical',
    appLink: '/tools/contributions',
    appLinkLabel: 'Contributions Tracker',
    requirements: [
      'SSS number and My.SSS account',
      'Knowledge of your current MSC bracket (check your contribution record at my.sss.gov.ph)',
      'For voluntary contributions: bank account or payment channel',
    ],
    steps: [
      'Log in to My.SSS at member.sss.gov.ph and check your Contribution Record',
      'Identify your current Monthly Salary Credit (MSC) — is it at the maximum bracket?',
      'If employed: verify with HR that your SSS contribution is based on your ACTUAL monthly salary, not a lower amount',
      'If self-employed/voluntary: go to My.SSS → Payment Reference Number (PRN) → select a higher contribution amount',
      'The maximum MSC as of 2025 is ₱30,000 (with plans to increase to ₱35,000). Aim for this bracket if you can afford it',
      'Set up auto-debit for consistent monthly payments — gaps in contributions reduce your pension',
      'Track your contributions monthly using the Sandalan Contributions Tracker',
    ],
    fees: 'Employee share: 4.5% of MSC (employer pays 9.5%). Self-employed/voluntary: 14% of declared MSC. At maximum MSC ₱30,000: ₱4,200/month total contribution',
    processingTime: 'Contribution updates take effect on the next payment cycle. Contribution records update within 1-2 months',
    tips: [
      'Check for gaps in your contribution history — you may be able to fill some gaps through voluntary payments',
      'If you\'re self-employed, declare a higher Monthly Salary Credit even if your income varies — a higher AMSC means a higher pension',
      'The Pension Booster program allows additional voluntary contributions above the regular maximum — ask at any SSS branch',
      'Continue contributing even after reaching the minimum 120 months — more years of contributions = higher pension',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'SSS Member Portal', url: 'https://member.sss.gov.ph/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'SSS Contribution Table', url: 'https://www.sss.gov.ph/'),
    ],
  ),
  'passive-income-source': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'passive-income-source',
    title: 'Set up passive income source',
    description: 'Passive income — money earned with minimal ongoing effort — is the key to a comfortable retirement and financial freedom.',
    why: 'Your SSS pension won\'t be enough. Active income (salary) stops when you retire. Passive income continues flowing whether you work or not. Starting in your 40s-50s gives you 10-20 years to build income streams that will sustain you in retirement.',
    how: 'Choose one or more passive income sources and start building them now: rental property income, stock dividends, Pag-IBIG MP2 staggered withdrawals, UITF distributions, or a small business that can run without your daily involvement.',
    priority: 'important',
    appLink: '/goals',
    appLinkLabel: 'Set Passive Income Goal',
    requirements: [
      'Capital to invest (varies by income source)',
      'Time to set up and establish the income stream (1-5 years)',
      'Basic financial literacy (understanding of returns, risks, and taxes)',
    ],
    steps: [
      'Assess how much passive income you need: total retirement expenses − SSS pension − other guaranteed income = passive income target',
      'Choose your income source(s) based on available capital and risk tolerance',
      'Rental property: Purchase a rental unit in a high-demand area. Budget for maintenance, vacancy periods, and property management. Net yield: 3-6% of property value annually',
      'Dividend stocks: Build a portfolio of blue-chip dividend-paying stocks (SM, BDO, PLDT, Globe). Target: 3-5% dividend yield',
      'Pag-IBIG MP2: Open multiple MP2 accounts in staggered years (one maturing each year). Tax-free 6-7% returns',
      'Bond investments: Retail Treasury Bonds (RTBs) pay regular coupon interest. Government-guaranteed',
      'Start with whatever amount you can — even ₱5,000/month invested consistently grows to a substantial passive income source over 10-15 years',
    ],
    tips: [
      'Diversify your passive income — don\'t rely on a single source',
      'Rental property requires active management (or a property manager). It\'s not truly "passive" unless you hire help',
      'Reinvest passive income until retirement to accelerate growth through compounding',
      'Start small and scale up — buy your first dividend stock, open your first MP2 account, then grow from there',
      'Track all passive income in Sandalan to see your progress toward financial freedom',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'Pag-IBIG MP2 Program', url: 'https://www.pagibigfund.gov.ph/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'PSE Listed Companies', url: 'https://www.pse.com.ph/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'Bureau of the Treasury', url: 'https://www.treasury.gov.ph/'),
    ],
  ),
  'advance-healthcare-directive': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'advance-healthcare-directive',
    title: 'Create advance healthcare directive',
    description: 'An advance healthcare directive (living will) specifies your medical treatment preferences if you become unable to communicate — ensuring your wishes are followed.',
    why: 'If you suffer a stroke, fall into a coma, or develop severe dementia, you may be unable to make medical decisions. Without a directive, your family must guess what you would want — leading to agonizing decisions, family disagreements, and potentially unwanted medical interventions.',
    how: 'Write a document specifying your wishes regarding life-sustaining treatments, resuscitation, organ donation, and who should make medical decisions on your behalf. While the Philippines doesn\'t have a specific advance directive law, such documents are recognized under general principles of medical ethics and patient autonomy.',
    priority: 'important',
    requirements: [
      'Clear understanding of your healthcare preferences',
      'A trusted person to designate as your healthcare proxy',
      'Consultation with your physician about realistic medical scenarios',
      'Notarization (recommended for stronger legal standing)',
    ],
    steps: [
      'Discuss with your doctor: Understand the common medical scenarios for your age and health conditions',
      'Decide on your preferences: Do you want CPR if your heart stops? Mechanical ventilation? Tube feeding? Dialysis? These are the key decisions',
      'Choose a healthcare proxy: A trusted person (spouse, adult child, sibling) who will make medical decisions if you cannot',
      'Write the directive: Include your full name, date, specific medical preferences, healthcare proxy details, and your signature',
      'Have the document notarized for stronger legal standing',
      'Give copies to: your healthcare proxy, your primary physician, and your family. Keep the original in your personal files',
      'Review and update the directive every 2-3 years or after any major health diagnosis',
    ],
    tips: [
      'Have an honest conversation with your family about your wishes — the directive supports but doesn\'t replace open communication',
      'Include organ donation preferences if applicable — this is a separate consent in the Philippines (RA 7170)',
      'Keep a card in your wallet indicating you have an advance directive and who your healthcare proxy is',
      'Your directive can be changed or revoked at any time while you are competent',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'Philippine Medical Association', url: 'https://www.philippinemedicalassociation.org/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'DOH (Department of Health)', url: 'https://doh.gov.ph/'),
    ],
  ),
  'consolidate-bank-accounts': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'consolidate-bank-accounts',
    title: 'Consolidate bank accounts',
    description: 'Most people accumulate 3-6 bank accounts over their career. Consolidating to 2-3 accounts reduces fees, simplifies tracking, and makes estate settlement easier for your family.',
    why: 'Dormant accounts incur monthly fees (₱300-₱500/month). Multiple accounts make budgeting harder, increase the risk of forgotten balances, and complicate estate settlement. Simplification saves money and gives you a clearer financial picture.',
    how: 'Identify all your bank accounts, determine which to keep (primary expenses + savings + investments), transfer balances, update all auto-debits and direct deposits, then formally close the redundant accounts at the branch.',
    priority: 'good-to-have',
    requirements: [
      'List of all your bank accounts (check old IDs, statements, and mobile apps)',
      'Valid government ID for branch visits',
      'Checkbook/debit card/passbook for accounts to close',
    ],
    steps: [
      'Create a complete list of all bank accounts: savings, checking, time deposits, dormant accounts, joint accounts',
      'Identify which accounts to keep: one primary account (salary/pension), one high-yield savings (emergency/medical fund), one investment account (if needed)',
      'Transfer all balances from accounts you\'re closing to your primary account',
      'Update auto-debits, direct deposits, and linked services (bills, subscriptions, e-wallets) to your primary account',
      'Wait 30 days to ensure all pending transactions have cleared',
      'Visit each bank branch to formally close the account — bring your ID, passbook/card, and account closure form',
      'Keep the closure confirmation document for your records',
    ],
    fees: 'Account closure: Free for most banks. Some charge ₱300–₱500 for early closure (within 30-90 days of opening). Dormant account reactivation: ₱300–₱500',
    processingTime: 'Account closure: same day. Balance transfers: instant (same bank) or 1-3 business days (inter-bank)',
    tips: [
      'Check for dormant accounts — banks charge monthly dormancy fees, and after 10 years of dormancy, balances are escheated to the Philippine government',
      'Before closing a payroll account: ensure your employer has your new account details and has processed at least one salary payment to the new account',
      'Keep at least one account in a major bank (BDO, BPI, Metrobank) for accessibility — they have the most ATMs and branches',
      'Digital bank accounts (Maya, CIMB, Tonik) don\'t need to be consolidated — they have no maintaining balance or fees',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'BSP Consumer Protection', url: 'https://www.bsp.gov.ph/'),
    ],
  ),

  // ─── Phase 8: Gintong Taon (Golden Years) ──────────────────────────────────
  'senior-citizen-id': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'senior-citizen-id',
    title: 'Get senior citizen ID',
    description: 'The Senior Citizen ID is your key to the 20% mandatory discount, 12% VAT exemption, free movies, priority lanes, and all benefits under Republic Act 9994.',
    why: 'Without the Senior Citizen ID, you cannot claim any of the benefits under RA 9994. The 20% discount on medicine alone can save ₱10,000–₱30,000/year for seniors with maintenance medications. It\'s free to get and valid nationwide.',
    how: 'Visit the Office for Senior Citizens Affairs (OSCA) at your city or municipal hall. Bring a valid ID showing your date of birth, proof of residence, and a recent photo. Registration is free and usually completed same day.',
    priority: 'critical',
    requirements: [
      'Any valid government-issued ID showing date of birth (must be 60+)',
      'Proof of residence: barangay certificate, utility bill, or voter\'s ID',
      '1x1 or 2x2 ID photo (recent, colored)',
      'Accomplished OSCA registration form (available at the office)',
    ],
    steps: [
      'Visit the Office for Senior Citizens Affairs (OSCA) at your city or municipal hall',
      'Get and fill out the Senior Citizen registration form',
      'Submit the form with your valid ID, proof of residence, and ID photo',
      'Wait for processing — most OSCA offices issue the ID on the same day or within 1-2 weeks',
      'Receive your Senior Citizen ID and booklet for recording purchases',
      'Present the ID at any establishment to claim your 20% discount and VAT exemption',
      'If you cannot go personally due to health reasons: designate a representative with a notarized Special Power of Attorney (SPA)',
    ],
    fees: 'FREE — Senior Citizen ID registration has no fees. Do not pay any fixer or middleman',
    processingTime: 'Same day to 2 weeks, depending on your LGU',
    tips: [
      'Get the ID as soon as you turn 60 — don\'t wait. Every day without it is money left on the table',
      'Keep the ID with you at all times — you never know when you\'ll need the discount',
      'The Senior Citizen booklet helps track your purchases and discounts — keep it updated for your records',
      'Report any establishment that refuses to honor the senior citizen discount to OSCA or DTI',
      'If you\'re a dual citizen or returning OFW, you are still eligible for the Senior Citizen ID if you\'re 60+ and residing in the Philippines',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'RA 9994 (Expanded Senior Citizens Act)', url: 'https://www.lawphil.net/statutes/repacts/ra2010/ra_9994_2010.html'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'DSWD OSCA Information', url: 'https://www.dswd.gov.ph/'),
    ],
  ),
  'claim-sss-pension': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'claim-sss-pension',
    title: 'Claim SSS retirement pension',
    description: 'Your SSS retirement pension is a monthly income for life — but you must actively file a claim to start receiving it. SSS does not automatically pay you.',
    why: 'Many retirees delay filing their pension claim, losing months of payments. SSS pension is retroactive only to the month of filing — if you wait 6 months after turning 60, you lose 6 months of pension. File early.',
    how: 'File your retirement claim online through My.SSS or at any SSS branch. You need at least 120 monthly contributions to qualify. Optional retirement starts at 60 (if separated from employment), mandatory at 65.',
    priority: 'critical',
    appLink: '/tools/contributions',
    appLinkLabel: 'Contributions Tracker',
    requirements: [
      'At least 120 monthly SSS contributions',
      'SSS E-1 form (Personal Record) and E-4 form (Beneficiary Record)',
      'PSA-authenticated birth certificate',
      'Two valid government IDs',
      'Savings account passbook or ATM card for pension deposit',
      'Separation from employment (for optional retirement at 60)',
    ],
    steps: [
      'Verify your contribution record at my.sss.gov.ph — ensure you have at least 120 monthly contributions',
      'Check that your E-1 and E-4 records are updated and accurate',
      'File the retirement claim: online through My.SSS or in person at any SSS branch',
      'Submit all required documents (birth certificate, IDs, bank account details)',
      'Wait for processing: 1-3 months from complete submission',
      'Receive your first pension payment via direct deposit to your designated bank account',
      'You will also receive a 13th month pension every December',
    ],
    fees: 'Free — there are no fees to file a retirement claim',
    processingTime: '1-3 months from complete submission. First pension retroactive to month of filing',
    tips: [
      'File 1-3 months before your intended retirement date — don\'t wait until after you stop working',
